<HEADLINE> Zaire Peace Talks Scheduled Later This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited peace talks
between the Zairean government and rebels are scheduled to take
place in South Africa later this week, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Pretoria, spokesman for the
Department of Foreign Affairs Marco Boni said his Department
would not provide details of the proposed talks, such as venues
and logistics of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Boni said it was up to the negotiating parties to release the
information.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said United Nations special envoy for the
Great Lakes region Mohamed Sahnoun would lead the talks, which
were tentatively scheduled for Saturday in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The talks are expected to get under way most likely this
weekend," U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said in New York.
</P>
<P>
Zairean rebels on Monday reportedly said they were ready for
talks with representatives of President Mobutu Sese Seko as early
as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The South African government, which had been in contact with
the two warring parties, in a statement earlier welcomed
announcements by the two sides that they were prepared to engage
in direct negotiations and confirmed its willingness to
facilitate the talks.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government regards the proposed
negotiations between the conflicting parties in Zaire as being of
the utmost importance for a peaceful solution to the on-going
conflict in the Great Lakes region," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
