<HEADLINE> Southern African Leaders to Discuss Trade in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Regional leaders and business
executives will meet here next month to discuss strategies
southern Africa can take to attract investment and boost trade,
an official of the World Economic Forum (WEF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-based WEF, co-organizers of the southern Africa
economic summit, to be held from May 21 to 23, said delegates
would this year focus on the key issues of trade, the region's
competitiveness, infrastructure development and privatization.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela has accepted the
invitation to open the summit in his capacity as Chairman of the
12-member Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba, Botswana President Ketumile Masire, Mozambican
Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi and his Namibian counterpart Hage
Geingob will also attend the summit, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was estimated that 400 international chief
executives, 100 regional government and political leaders and
another 100 experts and media leaders would attend the summit,
the fifth to be held in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
