<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Backs Russia-Belarus Union Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today stated clearly that he supports a union of his country with
neighboring Belarus despite heated debates among Russian media and
political figures that such a union could be too costly for Russia.
</P>
<P>
"President Yeltsin states clearly and unequivocally that he is
an initiator of the unification of the two fraternal states and
their peoples, a consistent and firm supporter of it," said
Yeltsin's press secretary Sergi Yastrzhembsky at today's news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky said Yeltsin plans to sign the Union Treaty with
Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko on Wednesday and initial
a charter which will later be offered for public discussion in
both countries before ratification.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky said that public discussion "does not mean a
referendum."
</P>
<P>
Under the Russia-Belarus Union Treaty, the two countries will
remain independent but coordinate their foreign, economic and
military policies closely.
</P>
<P>
President Yeltsin gave the green light to the treaty on Monday,
and was expected to sign it on April 3 with his Belarussian
counterpart Lukashenko, Russian media reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
