<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Easter Road Death Toll Exceeds 300 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The death toll on South
African roads at the Easter weekend has reached 301, surpassing
last year's figure of 264 and costing the country more than 62
million Rand (about 14 Million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the National Traffic Information Center (NTIC)
Marleen Leita said here today that "we are shocked at the high
fatality figures for the Easter weekend."
</P>
<P>
The loss of life over this past weekend was a national
tragedy, she said, noting this country "can ill afford to spend"
the money resulted from these kind of head-on collisions.
</P>
<P>
On provincial base with regard to fatality figures, Eastern
Cape took the lead of 51, followed by Mpumalanga with 49, Free
State 46, Kwazulu/Natal 36, Gauteng 32, Northern Province 28,
Western Cape 27, Northwest 19 and Northern Cape 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
