<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan Parliament Decides to Scrap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Both houses of Pakistan's
parliament today adopted a key constitutional amendment bill,
scrapping controversial portions of the Eighth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment Bill, unanimously passed by the National
Assembly and the Senate in one day, divests the president of his
powers to dissolve the National Assembly and dismiss the
government.
</P>
<P>
One of the annulled clauses of the Eighth Amendment had
empowered the president to dissolve the National Assembly when "a
situation has arisen in which the government of the federation
cannot be carried on in accordance with the provisions of the
Constitution and an appeal to the electorate is necessary."
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment Bill also repeals an article of the
constitution regarding the appointment of provincial governors.
The governors would now be appointed on the advice of the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the new bill takes away powers of the governor to
dissolve the provincial assembly and, through an amendment to
another article of the constitution, withdraws the powers of the
president to appoint "in his discretion" the Chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff Committee and Service Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Assembly after the passage of the
bill, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said the unanimous adoption of
the bill had restored the spirit of the parliamentary system.
</P>
<P>
The move was in fact a reflection of the consent of the whole
nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sharif announced in the Senate that a cross party
constitutional reform committee for reviewing the controversial
clauses of the constitution would be formed.
</P>
<P>
The committee would recommend a package of constitutional
reforms, he said, adding that in future all political parties
would be involved in matters of national importance.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Benazir Bhutto, also chairperson of the
Pakistan People's Party, called the passage of the 13th Amendment
a positive step.
</P>
<P>
She said that a strong leadership was essential for the
increase of trade and exports and it would now be provided by the
office of the Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of other political parties also lauded the revocation
of the Eighth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
It would help strengthen the country's democratic institutions
and put democracy on a proper path, they said.
</P>
<P>
The infamous Eighth Amendment was inserted in the constitution
in 1985 by the partyless parliament during the rule of the late
President Zia-ul Haq.
</P>
<P>
Its most controversial provision has since been used four times
to dismiss elected governments and has been a source of constant
political instability.
</P>
<P>
Under the Eighth Amendment, the president had discretionary
powers to dismiss the government and the National Assembly,
appoint services chiefs, the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff
committee and the chief election commissioner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
