<HEADLINE> India, Oman Agree to Strengthen Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- India and Oman today agreed to
further consolidate bilateral cooperation in economic, political
and cultural fields, Press Trust of India (PTI) said.
</P>
<P>
Sultan Qaboos Bin Said of Oman, who arrived here today on a
four-day state visit, proposed a strategic alliance in trade and
investment with India during his talks with Indian President
Shanker Dayal Sharma and Vice President K.R. Narayanan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a banquet given in his honor, the Sultan said his
first ever state visit to India served to further enhance
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Sharma, in his speech at the banquet, conveyed to the
Sultan New Delhi's desire to become a dialogue partner of the Gulf
Cooperation Council to promote mutual understanding and help
realize the inherent potential for joint cooperation, according to
PTI.
</P>
<P>
The Sultan, who is leading a high-level delegation including 14
of his ministers, was originally scheduled to come here last
month. The visit was postponed due to bad weather in Muscat,
capital of Oman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
