<HEADLINE> Greece, Uzbekistan Sign Agreements to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Uzbekistan signed here
today several cooperation agreements to strengthen the bilateral
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The seven agreements were signed by Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis and visiting Uzbek President Islam Karimov while the two
had talks which lasted over one hour.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed include a bilateral friendship and
cooperation accord and six separate ones which provide for
cooperation in tourism, education, professional training,
technology, culture and the avoidance of double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Simitis hailed the
agreements signed today as a "springboard" for closer ties and
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need of furthering and strengthening
Athens' relations with all the countries in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, President Karimov described his talks
with Simitis as "fruitful and constructive".
</P>
<P>
Karimov expressed his hope that there was plenty of room for
Athens and Tashkent to further develop bilateral ties because the
two shared the same views on all issues.
</P>
<P>
Uzbekistan was interested in broadening its ties not only with
Greece but also with the European Union (EU), he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also praised Athens for the important role it is
playing and could play in the future in the Balkans and central
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Karimov, who arrived here yesterday for a two-day official
visit to Athens, had already held talks early today with his Greek
counterpart, Kostis Stephanopoulos, to discuss how to boost
bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
