<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Politicians Divided Over Russia-Belarus Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian politicians have divergent
views on the Russia-Belarus Union Treaty, which was signed today
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his Belarusian counterpart,
Alexander Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
Boris Nemtsov, the newly-appointed first deputy prime minister,
warned Monday that the treaty should not hurt the people of the
two countries economically, politically or socially.
</P>
<P>
He said that it's better to leave a leeway to improve the union
treaty rather than being rash to sign it.
</P>
<P>
Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the liberal
Yavlinsky-Boldyrev-Lukin (Yabloko), also said today that time was
not ripe for signing the treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said that unification on the basis of the treaty is likely
to make the economic and political situation worse both in Russia
and Belarus, adding that the union treaty still needs details
added to all the provisions.
</P>
<P>
However, Speaker of the Russian State Duma Gennady Seleznyov
said today that the Russia-Belarus Union would be the first phase
of creating a confederation of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov said that the Duma is likely to ratify the treaty
after a debate on April 9.
</P>
<P>
He added that the door to the Russia-Belarus Union would be
open to any other willing member nations of the CIS (Commonwealth
of Independent States).
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Lukyanov, Chairman of the Committee on Legislation and
Court Reform of the Duma, told the Itar-Tass news agency today
that the union is bound to be realized in any form despite
opposition from some people.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the creation of the union is also a step
designed to counter the eastward enlargement of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Denying the claims that the signing of the treaty was
overhasty, Lukyanov said that everything had been planned a year
before and "we have been ready for the Russia-Belarus Union long
ago."
</P>
<P>
Sergei Dubinin, governor of Russia's Central Bank, said that it
would take at least several years to form a unified currency for
the Russia-Belarus Union and the Russian rouble is most likely to
become the single currency of the union.
</P>
<P>
He said that the signing of the treaty would not have immediate
negative economic consequences in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in Fire Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen Israeli soldiers were
wounded today when the bus they were traveling caught fire and
overturned after attacked by a petrol bomb thrown by Palestinian
protesters.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred this afternoon when the bus was
traveling on the road near a Palestinian refugee camp in northern
Ramallah, north of Jerusalem. The driver got burnt after the
petrol bomb attack and lost control of the bus, which crashed
down to the roadside and overturned.
</P>
<P>
An army spokesman said that 13 Israeli soldiers suffered
light to moderate injuries from the incident. They were
evacuated to a Jerusalem hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops immediately imposed a curfew in the area and
began investigation into the attack. Israel army denounced the
incident as a "serious escalation" of the Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between Palestinian stone-throwers and Israeli soldiers
continued today across the West Bank following two suicide
bombings in the Gaza Strip Tuesday and the death of two
Palestinians shot by Israeli border policemen in the West Bank
cities of Nablus and Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In Nablus, over 1,000 Palestinians held protests over the
death of a policeman who was shot dead by Israeli soldiers when
he took part in a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Israel stationed tanks, armed personnel carriers and snipers
outside Nablus as precaution against possible escalation of
violence. Nablus witnessed the bloodiest clash during late last
September's Israeli-Palestinian bloodshed, in which six Israeli
soldiers guarding the holy Jewish site of Joseph's Tomb were
killed by Palestinian protesters.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli woman was lightly wounded near Ramallah when her
car was hit by stones thrown by Palestinian protesters. An
Israeli girl was also slightly hurt near Bethlehem as her
mother's car came under stone attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
