<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Pressure Israel Back to Peace Track: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt
Mohamed Sobeih said today that the Arab stance would pressure the
Israeli leadership to return to the regional peace track and
abide by agreements.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with an Egyptian T.V. program, he accused the
Israeli government led by Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu of
"destroying all bridges of confidence and poisoning the
atmosphere of peace."
</P>
<P>
He said the Arabs have stepped up efforts to pressure Israel
to reverse the decision last month to go ahead with a 6,500-unit
Jewish settlement at Har Homa in disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The recent move is the Arab League resolutions calling for a
freeze in relations with Israel and reactivation of the Arab
economic boycott of Israel, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is an occupied Arab land, that is why Israel should
never be allowed to build, even one house, in it or to change its
demographic status," Sobeih said.
</P>
<P>
"Israel must understand that the Arabs would never give up or
forgo their rights," he added.
</P>
<P>
He described as very strong the recent European Union
statement calling upon Israel to respect international
resolutions so as to straighten things up.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official stressed the importance of the role
played by Europe in the peace process and urged the EU to cut its
trade transactions with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Europe can put an end to the Israeli arrogance and conceit
through curbing its trade relations with the Jewish state," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to save Jerusalem from all measures that would change
its position and preempt serious negotiations on its status," he
said. "The resolution on Jerusalem approved by the Arab League
Council meeting Monday has carved out such a clear Arab stance."
</P>
<P>
The Arabs have decided to stop normal relations, revive
economic boycott, close down Israeli missions and withdraw from
Mideast multilateral talks, in the strongest concerted step they
have taken since the Netanyahu government took office last June.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have rejected security cooperation with
Israel and demanded it to give up the Jewish housing project on
disputed land in East Jerusalem, where they want to establish a
future capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel said peace talks can not continue until Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat gave an effective red
light to violence, including West Bank stone throwing riots and
suicide bombings by Islamic militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
