<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabe's Tombstone Arrives in Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The tombstone of John H.D. Rabe,
who witnessed the Nanjing Massacre led by invading Japanese
military forces, arrived in Nanjing today from Berlin, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The tombstone of black granite, 91 cm x 50 cm, will be placed
in the Jiangdongmen Museum for the massacre victims, said Zhu
Chengshan, director of the memorial hall.
</P>
<P>
Rabe came to China in 1908 and served as the general
representative of Germany's Siemens Company. He was elected
chairman of International Committee of the Nanjing Safety Zone
when Japan invade the city. He housed 250,000 refugees in the zone
and protected more than 10,000 women from being violated by
Japanese soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Rabe left China for Germany in 1938 and died in 1951. His
wartime diaries, in which he recorded in great detail the Japanese
soldiers' crimes, were preserved and made public by his
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
His relatives decided early this year to donate the diaries to
the museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
