<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Hampers Asia's Aquaculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Increasingly polluted waters,
razing of mangrove habitats and high cost of feeds have adversely
affected Asia's fast-growing fish-farm harvests, a FAO press
release said today.
</P>
<P>
In the past 11 years, Asia's aquaculture expanded sevenfold,
and five countries -- the Philippines, China, India, Japan and
South Korea -- supply 80 percent of the world's harvests, mostly
carp, according to the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO).
</P>
<P>
However, these bumper harvests have entailed "environmental
pay-offs" that are becoming onerous, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
Other problems Asian fish-farmers face are disease outbreaks
because of poor water and soil condition and toxic contamination.
</P>
<P>
In some Asian countries and regions, their coasts are crowded
with high densities of cages and rafts. Restricted circulation of
ocean waters into and out of the East Asian seas makes them
particularly sensitive to environmental changes.
</P>
<P>
In some Southeast Asian countries, industrial complexes near
coastal areas spew sewage and chemicals into the waters.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these adverse factors, exports of shrimp and
fish products by South and Southeast Asian countries are falling.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the radical shrinkage of biologically-diverse
mangrove forests, this region today faces other threats:
salination of groundwater and farm lands, destruction of habitats
for "wild-seed" shrimp larvae and poorly-fished coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
Public perception of aquaculture might be damaged by the
irresponsible practices of some entrepreneurs who have caused
serious environmental degradation and social disruption, it said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
