<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Thai Prime Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng and Thai
Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, in a session of formal talks
here today, expressed the conviction that China and
Thailand should foster closer good-neighborly ties of all-round
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Li voiced satisfaction with what he called
"fruitful cooperation" between China and Thailand over the years.
</P>
<P>
Describing Chavalit as "an old friend of China," Li said he
expected the Thai prime minister's China visit to be successful,
and the friendship between the two countries and peoples to
further develop.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said he was happy to meet Li in Beijing. He told Li
that many government ministers and military officers have come
with him on the visit, with the aim of strengthening bilateral
cooperation in wide-ranging fields.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers observed that as diplomatic ties enter
the third decade, the two countries are enjoying sound political
relations along with smooth exchanges in economy, culture and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
The last few years have witnessed a large increase in the
bilateral trade volume, vibrant mutual investment and a good
beginning in financial exchanges, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers said they believe the sustained
economic growth of China and Thailand will produce more
opportunities and favorable conditions for bilateral trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li and Chavalit discussed ways to expand and deepen cooperation
in waterpower, railway, oceangoing transportation, mutual
investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
Li said the Chinese Government holds a positive attitude toward
cooperation in these fields, and supports efforts made by Chinese
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit noted Thai businessmen have a strong interest in
investing in China, and Thailand would like to see Chinese
enterprises take part in Thailand's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and Thai prime ministers also authorized their
related ministers to further study and carry out specific projects
of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit congratulated Li on China's resuming exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1. He said he is confident in
Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return, the Chinese premier stressed, China
will guarantee Hong Kong's prosperity and stability and protect
the lawful interests of foreign countries there, including those
of Thailand, by unswervingly pursuing the "one country, two
systems" policy initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit reiterated the Thai Government takes the "one China"
stance -- a policy it has pursued over the years. Li thanked the
Thai Government for backing China's position on questions, such as
the Taiwan issue, that concern China's sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit was happy to see that China has become a full dialogue
partner of the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations),
saying that it is recognized by the world that China is enjoying a
closer relationship with the organization and a higher status in
the international and regional arena.
</P>
<P>
Li noted China pursues a good-neighborly policy of peace and
attaches great importance to its relations with Thailand and
cooperation with the ASEAN. It is willing to work with Thailand
and other ASEAN nations for the peace, stability and prosperity of
the region and the world as a whole, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit extended an invitation to Li for a second trip to
Thailand, which met with Li's appreciation.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit arrived this afternoon on an official visit to China
at the invitation of Li.  
</P>
</TEXT>
