<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Success, Problems Mixed in China's Social Guarantee System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Reform of China's social guarantee
has made marked progress in the past decade and more, but problems
still exist, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The original social guarantee system in China, established under
and tailored to a planned economy, no longer accords with the
needs of the country's socialist market economy, Du Jian, director
of Social Guarantee Department under the Ministry of Finance, told
an international seminar on social guarantee funds management,
which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the issue, China began to reform its old social
guarantee system in 1986. To date, China has launched an extensive
reform in introducing a pooling pension system for employees of
urban-based enterprises and implemented pilot pension schemes in
some rural areas.
</P>
<P>
China's other achievements in reforming social guarantee
include the establishment of an unemployment insurance system and
an overall social planning system for unemployment insurance,
reforms in the health insurance system, the setting up of the
social welfare network in urban and township areas, and the
strengthened administration and supervision of the management of
social guarantee funds, according to Du.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that a total of 89.93 million people
had been covered by the overall social planning system by the end
of 1995 -- about 79.3 percent of China's workforce in
enterprises. Meanwhile, the system had also covered 23.1 million
retirees, about 97.6 percent of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, a total of 82.71 million enterprise
employees across China had been covered by the unemployment
insurance service, accounting for 72.8 percent of the total
workforce. A total of 1.53 million employees had received
unemployment relief.
</P>
<P>
Official data also show that the social guarantee system of a
minimum living standard had been introduced in about 100 cities
throughout China.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid growth of a rural economy, the all-round
implementation of a family planning program and the demographic
changes, the previous pension system featuring the family security
concept for the rural areas could no longer meet the needs of
Chinese farmers.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the Chinese government decided to introduce on a trial
basis in some prosperous rural areas a pension plan of personal
savings. By the end of 1995, the program had been tested in more
than 1,500 counties across China, covering more than 50 million
farmers.
</P>
<P>
After more than ten years of reform, a social guarantee system
with Chinese characteristics which is fit for the market economy
has taken shape, Du said.
</P>
<P>
"However, as China's administrative control system and economic
mechanism are undergoing reform and readjustment, the social
guarantee system faces many problems," he said, referring to
increasing pressures from an aging population and unemployment,
and also to the fact that the distribution of national income has
been more focused on the individuals, making the state finance and
enterprises relatively financially difficult.
</P>
<P>
According to World Bank statistics, people over age 60 in 1990
accounted for an average of 6.8 percent of the total population in
Asia and 8.9 percent in China.
</P>
<P>
The ratio will be as high as 18 percent by the year 2026, when
China will have one quarter of the world's total elderly
population, the World Bank predicts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
