<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expert Put Forwards New Agricultural Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese expert recently put
forward a new theory for agricultural development that increased
benefits would accrue if farmers harvested stems and leaves
instead of seeds or fruits of some crops.
</P>
<P>
Yan Guangcai, a researcher in Beijing, said that plant stems
and leaves usually have much more nutritive value than the
traditional "crops"-- seeds or fruits.
</P>
<P>
"For example, if flowering soybean sprouts were gathered
instead of soybeans months later, and the fresh sprouts were
processed into good-quality fodders, the total benefit from per
unit land area would almost double," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The key technology of this `soybean sprout pattern' is to
process the fresh sprouts into all kinds of fodders without losing
much of their nutritive value. This has already been settled,
technically," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yan said, the fodders produced by this means can decrease stock
raising cost by 30 percent, and save half the crops.
</P>
<P>
Yan said that in many places of China, crops can be only
harvested once due to climate reasons. But planting another crop
of soybeans during the short growing season after the wheat
harvest will increase the total output and the farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
"In flood-struck areas without enough time for another crop of
wheat, a crop of soybean sprout will be a wise choice," Yan
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
