<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Belarus Sign Union Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his Belarusian counterpart Alexander Lukashenko today signed a
treaty on Russia-Belarus integration, turning the two countries
into a union.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also initialled the Charter of the Union, to
be discussed publicly in the two countries, and signed a
memorandum of understanding, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was attended by Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin, Belarusian Prime Minister Sergei Ling and
other senior officials from both sides.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Supreme Council of the Russia-Belarus
Community before the signing, Yeltsin said that "the union of
Belarus and Russia does not create a single state. Both sides
preserve their own sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the treaty is aimed at forming a union to
expand and strengthen the cooperation in security and border
guarding of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the people of the two countries would scrutinize
and implement the Union Charter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
