<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Hosts Seminar on Occupational Safety, Health Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A seminar on occupational safety
 and health was held here today as part of a campaign to promote a
 proposed legislation extending safety and health protection to
the non-industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
The Occupational Safety and Health Bill was introduced into the
 Legislative Council last December and is expected to be formally
endorsed in the second quarter of this year, Hong Kong
Commissioner for Labor Jacqueline Willis told the seminar.
</P>
<P>
"Once passed, we shall have an ordinance offering safety and
health protection to employees from all sectors," she said.
</P>
<P>
At present only workers of industrial undertakings are
protected, mainly through the Factories and Industrial
Undertakings Ordinance and its subsidiary legislation.
</P>
<P>
Willis said the new bill is necessary partly because of the
economic restructuring in Hong Kong. For the past decade or so the
 number of those working in the non-industrial sector has
increased by 45 percent to hit 1.8 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, she said, "The number of accidents occurring in the
sector is also an area of concern." Injury cases from the less
hazardous sector made up one-third of all the injury cases
recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of the passage of the bill, the Labor
Department initiated a promotion campaign, sending by mail to all
employers an Occupational Safety and Health Bulletin, a 12-sheet
advertisement at metro stations, a radio and TV announcement, and
posters and leaflets.
</P>
<P>
Officials and experts from Britain, Australia and the Chinese
mainland also addressed the one-day meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
