<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Enhance IPR Protection Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government remains
totally committed and determined to do its utmost to put in place
the best intellectual property rights (IPR) protection in the
territory, a spokesman for the Trade and Industry Branch said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a reference made to Hong Kong's IPR protection in
the National Trade Estimates Report published by the US Trade
Representative on March 31, the spokesman said Hong Kong will
persist with its anti-piracy efforts under the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We will continue to work with copyright owners from
the United States and other countries and seek their support, such
as testifying in Hong Kong courts of law."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are very disappointed to see remarks in the report
claiming that the government action has had little demonstrable
impact."
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong has taken vigorous enforcement action
against copyright piracy activities at the importation, storage,
distribution and retail level.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1995, he said, the quantity and value of seizures
in connection with copyright offenses in 1996 have increased by
186 percent and 22 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 144 people were imprisoned for such offenses compared
with only 18 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
He said the Hong Kong Customs will continue to take vigorous
enforcement action to combat copyright piracy, adding that the
government has proposed in the Copyright Bill a number of new
legislative measures.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, Hong Kong will further increase the
manpower of the Intellectual Property Investigation Bureau of the
Hong Kong Customs by 24 posts in 1997-98.  
</P>
</TEXT>
