<HEADLINE> India, Oman Sign Seven Agreements to Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- India and Oman today signed
seven agreements, giving a new dimension to their ongoing
bilateral cooperation in hydro-carbon, trade and investment, civil
aviation and information sectors, the Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
Under one of the agreements, signed on the second day of a
state visit to India by Sultan Qaboos Bin Said of Oman, both
countries decided to set up a joint venture company for a 1.1
billion U.S. dollar urea project in Oman.
</P>
<P>
Among the others are an agreement on foreign investment
promotion and protection, an agreement on avoidance of double
taxation and a memorandum of understanding on cooperation in
information.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed an accord on cultural exchange, an
agreement on cooperation between the Indian Council of Agriculture
Research and the Oman Ministry of Agriculture, and an agreement on
civil aviation.
</P>
<P>
The Sultan, who arrived here on Tuesday for a four-day visit,
is leading a high-level delegation comprising 14 ministers.
</P>
</TEXT>
