<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Vows to Improve Services for Overseas-Funded Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Municipal Government vows
better services for overseas-funded enterprises to improve the
overall investment environment and attract more capital.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yucheng, vice mayor of Beijing, told local press today that
the foreign investment into Beijing witnessed steady increase in
recent years. Meanwhile, "it is the overall investment environment
rather than the preferential policy that counts more now for
overseas investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
As part of the efforts to improve the environment, relevant
governmental departments today announced to focus on curbing the
irrational administrative fares levied on overseas-funded
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The levies in the future will strictly abide by government
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The officials should show a unified certificate to the
enterprises and fill a form issued by the city's finance
department. The enterprises otherwise can refuse to pay the fares.
</P>
<P>
More works will or have been done in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, seven departments, including taxation,
finance, and customs, organized a unified annual checkup for
overseas-funded ventures, greatly simplifying the procedures.
</P>
<P>
Also, the city's foreign economic relations and trade
commission has organized service teams for the selected 40
projects with an investment over 30 million US dollars. "The staff
are designated to tackle any problem in the operation of these
projects," according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
Lu revealed that the municipal government is to issue local
regulations to encourage the overseas investment in hi-tech
industry and give preferential treatment for multinational
corporations to set up their regional headquarters in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has designated hi-tech industry, services trade,
modern agriculture, old enterprise renovation, old city
reconstruction, and construction of urban public utilities, as
future economic outlets, according to Lu.
</P>
<P>
Between 1979 and 1996, some 12,714 overseas-funded ventures
have registered in the capital city. The contractual investment
volume topped more than 20 billion US dollars, of which 10
billion dollars have already been in use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
