<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Center on Small Hydro-power Starts Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the United
Nations International Center on Small Hydro-power began today in
Hangzhou, capital of Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Arthur Holcombe, resident representative of the UN Development
Program (UNDP) Beijing Office; Bernabe Garcia, senior regional
officer (Asia and Pacific) of UNDP; M.D. Muntasser, President of
the International Energy Foundation, attended a ceremony today,
along with representatives of other foreign organizations and
Chinese government officials.
</P>
<P>
UN International Center on Small Hydro-power was established
at the proposal of 23 international organizations and the Chinese
Government in 1994. The center will be the first UN-affiliated
organization jointly built by UN and the Chinese Government.
</P>
<P>
The main tasks of the UN International Center on Small
Hydro-power is to conduct activities such as personnel training,
information exchange, and technological consultancy, with a view
to solving power shortage faced by two billion people in the
world, protecting the environment, and helping poverty-eradication
programs of different countries, thus ensuring all-round progress
in rural areas of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment, the center has constructed seven
regional sub-centers in the five continents and has formed an
international small hydro-power network that involves 126
international institutions and organizations of 62
countries. Also, it has launched programs to improve the
environment and eradicate poverty in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The building of the center in Hangzhou will cost 25 million
yuan and will be put into use at the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
