<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Painted Pottery Not Imported: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Painted pottery was not an import
from the West; Chinese painted-pottery culture moved from the east
to the west to meet with Western culture somewhere between
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region and the Mid-Asia.
</P>
<P>
This is a theory offered by Li Shuicheng, deputy director of
the Department of Archaeology at Beijing University, in his
doctoral dissertation. He even wrote the dates and routes of the
Chinese painted-pottery culture's movement westward.
</P>
<P>
Archaeological finds have shown that painted pottery originated
in China some 7,000 years ago. China is one of the origins of
painted pottery in the world.
</P>
<P>
China's painted-pottery culture was highly developed in the
Loess Plateau in the northwestern part of the country, due to the
prevalence of the Majiayao culture found in Gansu and Qinghai
provinces, also in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
Li's dissertation on types of painted pottery known as Banshan
and Machang -- two phases of the Majiayao culture, dating back
some 4,000-4,600 years -- pioneers China's study on the Majiayao
culture, which was first discovered 70 years ago.
</P>
<P>
His paper examines the change of shape and design of the
painted pottery. The alterations in shape are the result of
reformed technology, while design expressed the potters' view of
themselves and nature, Li says.
</P>
<P>
According to Li's study, the change of design on the painted
pottery came about more quickly than that of its shape, suggesting
a slow development in pottery-making technology.
</P>
<P>
Pottery-making skills dominated the area for a long period of
time, resulting in the popularity of painted pottery, Li says,
adding that painted pottery soon disappeared after hand
craftsmanship was replaced by the pottery wheel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0060 </DOCNO>
