<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Enterprises Urged to Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Four top-level governmental bodies
has jointly issued a set of regulations to further define the
responsibility of township businesses in the country's
environmental protection program, aiming at salvaging the
endangered natural resources in countryside.
</P>
<P>
Jointly promulgated by the State Environmental Protection
Bureau, Ministry of Agriculture, State Planning Commission and
State Economic and Trade Commission, the regulations require the
country's government leaders at county and township levels to keep
responsibility for protecting the environmental quality, and for
setting limits for the discharge volume of industrial wastes.
</P>
<P>
The regulations also stipulate that all the township
enterprises should meet the country's limit on waste discharge by
the year 2000. The governments at all levels should strengthen
their supervision on the implementation of the regulations in
township enterprises, and help the enterprises readjust their
manufacturing capacity to reduce the waste discharge.
</P>
<P>
The regulations say that local governments should shut down the
over-polluting enterprises such as the low-yield tannery, paper
mills with an annual output of 5,000 tons or below, illegal
pesticide makers, and the mining and chemical plants with low
technical benchmarks. From now on, any approval of the enterprises
of this kind will be outlawed here.
</P>
<P>
Also, the importing, processing, and using of solid wastes from
foreign countries will be strictly forbidden in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
To tighten the control of water pollution in the country's
major lakes and rivers, the regulations ban the launching of
chemical pulp factories, tanneries, dyeing mills, brewerys, and
electroplating plants in the valleys of Huaihe River, Haihe River,
Liaohe River, Taihu Lake, Chaohu Lake, and Dianchi Lake.
</P>
<P>
Besides monitoring the township enterprises in the
anti-pollution drive, the regulations also require the governments
at all levels to provide financial support for the "model
conservation projects" which will play an exemplary role in
promoting the pollution control technologies in the countryside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
