<HEADLINE> Japan Top Court Rules Donation to Yasukuni Unconstitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Supreme Court today ruled
that the Ehime prefectural government's donation of public money
to the Yasukuni Shrine from 1981 to 1986 violates the Constitution
which stipulates the separation of politics and religion.
</P>
<P>
It's the top court's first decision on the donation of
taxpayer's money to the shinto shrine in central Tokyo, according
the Kyodo News Service.
</P>
<P>
The ruling said that the donation violates Article 20 of the
Constitution, which stipulates "The state and its organs shall
refrain from religious activity." It's also against Article 89
which prohibits any public property from being used for any
religious institutions.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was made in response to a suit filed in 1982 by a
group of local residents in Ehime prefecture, southwestern Japan,
against then Ehime governor Haruki Shiraishi and several other
local officials for donating public money to the Yasukuni Shrine.
</P>
<P>
The Yasukuni Shrine houses the memorial tablets of Japan's war
dead since 19th century, including 14 class-A war criminals such
as Hideki Tojo.
</P>
<P>
Last July, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto made a
"private" visit to the shrine on his birthday, which prompted
strong protests from China, South Korea and other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The court ordered the Ehime officials to repay a total of
166,000 yen (1,300 U.S. dollars) donated from 1981 to 1986 as the
plaintiffs had demanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
