<HEADLINE> German Current Account Deficit Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Germany's current account deficit
rose to 9.3 billion marks (5.6 billion U.S. dollars) in January,
more than double the 4.1 billion marks (2.47 billion dollars)
registered in January last year, the German Federal Office of
Statistics in Wiesbaden said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The office blamed the current account deficit mainly on the
widening capital and investment deficit, which rose to 5.4 billion
marks (3.25 billion dollars) from 1.5 billion marks (900 million
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Other factors included high deficit in the service sector,
especially in travel and cash transfers.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by stronger foreign demand, German exports expanded to
64.4 billion marks (39 billion dollars) in January, up 5 percent
over the same time last year. Imports rose by 3.7 percent to 58.8
billion marks (35.4 billion dollars). 
</P>
