<HEADLINE> FIFA Secretariate Says More Players Cheat Referees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- International Football Federation
(FIFA) Secretary-general Sepp Blatter said in a FIFA newsletter
that players around the world are increasingly trying to cheat
referees.
</P>
<P>
Blatter also wrote in FIFA News that his organization is
against the use of video technology in matches.
</P>
<P>
"There is, in many countries, a growing tendency to deceive the
referee," Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
"When a professional star takes a dive, millions of lesser
players dive with him.
</P>
<P>
"All players, stars and amateurs alike, must acknowledge once
and for all that they cannot expect the referee to be sympathetic
to their cause when they repeatedly seek to mislead him by
simulating fouls and other tricks.
</P>
<P>
"For such behaviour has a name, and not a very pleasant one:
cheating. And referees, for all their human fallibility, do not
cheat."
</P>
<P>
Blatter said that the video technology, if introduced, would
change the face of football "drastically and irrevocably".
</P>
<P>
He said FIFA firmly believed that the game must continue to be
controlled by people and that human fallibility must remain a
feature of the game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
