<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Education Rules for China's Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Parents of China's 270 million
families will soon have a "guidebook" when they play the role of
educators at home.
</P>
<P>
The "guidebook" is a set of family education rules for parents
just issued by the State Education Commission (SEC) and the
All-China Women's Federation (ACWF).
</P>
<P>
The rules map out the most basic requirements of family
education for parents, including the parents' concept of family
education, attitude, and methods when they become teachers at home.
</P>
<P>
Parents are educating children for the country, said the rules,
and they should tell their children how to behave as upright
people. Parents are responsible to help children develop habits of
observing social ethics and increase their awareness of legal and
social responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The rules encourage parents to assign some chores to children
and support them to take part in public labor work. By doing so,
children are expected to be used to labor work and be
self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
Parents should love and care children and educate them
strictly. Parents should not spoil, spank, blame, or discriminate
against children. A fact that parents have to accept is that
children have their own independent personalities which need to be
respected. Children's legal rights and interests should be
protected.
</P>
<P>
An official from the SEC said here today that family education
is closely related to the national education and should be
regulated by laws and rules.
</P>
<P>
"The rules are a valuable attempt in regulating family
education," he said. China is turning to a more quality-emphasized
education from test-oriented one to release children from
intensive competition of examinations.
</P>
<P>
"We must have support from the parents to do so," he said. Once
the parents give up their strong wish of seeing their children
becoming extremely successful in life, children would have a much
more comfortable and democratic family atmosphere. School
education and family education would then be better combined and
become much more efficient, he said.
</P>
<P>
The rules asked parents to raise appropriate request toward
children's schoolwork in a proper way.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the rules were based on several Chinese laws,
including Marriage Law, Compulsory Education Law, Education Law,
Law on Protection of People under Age 18, and the UN Convention on
the Rights of Children.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
last summer showed that most Chinese parents really want to know
what are the best ways to tell their children what they should and
should not do, as over half say that they are not qualified
teachers at home.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that 96.2 percent of the parents polled
expressed an interest in learning how to teach their
children. There were even 4.1 percent of them saying they just did
not have the ability to educate their children.
</P>
<P>
The SEC and ACWF expecte wide promotion of the rules and
encourage parents across the country to participate in the
competition of "excellent parenting". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unique Oil Theory Boosts China's Oil Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China has developed an important
theory of the continental petroleum geology through 40 years of
research and experiments, which runs parallel to an influential
international theory on hydrocarbon formation of marine geology.
</P>
<P>
The theory has significantly boosted China's oil development,
said Li Tianxiang, chairman of the Science and Technology
Committee of the China National Petroleum Corp (CNPC), in an
interview with Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Using the theory, China has ascertained 27 large oilfields,
each with deposits above 100 million tons, including such
well-known oilfields as Daqing in northeast and Renqiu in north
China.
</P>
<P>
The official said that with exploration and practice, China has
finally developed layer-by-layer oil extraction technology,
stabilizing oil reserves with injected water, and using the
polymer-drive extraction method, which are comparable to advanced
methods used around the world.
</P>
<P>
Other major Chinese oilfields in the Bohai Bay areas, such as
Shengli, Liaohe, Zhongyuan, Huabei (North China), and Dagang have
developed rolling exploration technology, which has increased oil
exploration in the area.
</P>
<P>
So far the bay areas of the Bohai Sea have been found to have
proven oil deposits of 7.28 billion tons and annual crude output
of 61 million tons, making it the second largest oil and gas
production base after Daqing, he explained.
</P>
<P>
In the exploration of complex oil layers, China has come up
with a range of thermodynamic technologies to explore thick oil,
mainly by the use of steam.
</P>
<P>
The country has developed an annual thick oil output of 12
million tons, the fourth largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
A leading official with CNPC pointed out that China has set an
explicit target of proving 2.5 billion to 3 billion tons of oil
reserves by the turn of the century, and having annual oil and gas
output of 150 million tons and 25 billion cu m, respectively, by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
To meet the goal, the official noted that China is launching
eight huge petroleum science and technology projects, and 32
technological developments nationwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book on Ancient Lacquer in Hubei Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- An illustrated book on ancient
lacquers found in central China's Hubei Province, origin of
ancient Chu culture, has been published.
</P>
<P>
A combination of advanced coating and painting techniques in
the romantic style of the ancient Chu culture, they represent the
highest level of ancient Chinese lacquers.
</P>
<P>
With 300 color pictures, the book introduces some 114 lacquers
of the Chu State in the Eastern Zhou Dynasty (770-221 BC), 33 from
the Qin Dynasty (221-206 BC), and 61 from the Western Han Dynasty
(206 BC-24 AD).
</P>
<P>
The lacquers include such a famous national treasure as a
colorful food container in the shape of a mandarin duck, as well
as some 60 lacquers unearthed recently which have never been open
to the public.
</P>
<P>
Attached to the book is an essay written by Chen Zhenyu,
director of the provincial Institute of Archaeology.
</P>
<P>
A latest achievement in the study of ancient lacquers, the
essay tells how the lacquers were excavated, analyzes the
lacquer-making techniques, and the evolution of shape, structure,
design, decoration, painting and colors.
</P>
<P>
An invention of the Chinese people, lacquers played an important
role in social life during the Warring States Period (475-221 BC),
Qin Dynasty, and the Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD). Lacquer was
replaced by porcelain after the Three Kingdoms Period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
Hubei boosts the largest number of unearthed lacquers because
the local traditional burial system -- sealing the burial rooms
with white clay -- helped to preserve the easily damaged
lacquers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
