<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Poisoning Cases On Rise In Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Salmonella-related Food poisoning
cases had risen 47 percent in Australia's Queensland state over
the past three years, State Health Minister Mike Horan said today.
</P>
<P>
Horan said in a statement that it was estimated that more than
200,000 out of 3.2 million people in Queensland experienced a
salmonella-related food poisoning incident last year.
</P>
<P>
He said this was on the basis that for every single case of
salmonella notified to health authorities, there were around 100
cases not notified. Salmonella cases notified to Queensland health
authorities increased from 1367 cases in 1993 to 2,010 cases in
1996, according to him.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of national concern about the safety of food
following three serious salmonella outbreaks in Melbourne last
week, Horan called for increased vigilance by food handlers.
</P>
<P>
So far this year in just three months, 694 cases of
salmonella-related food poisoning have been notified in the state.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in salmonella-related food poisoning cases
highlights the tremendous need for increased vigilance along all
parts of the food chain," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he also stressed, it was important that members of the
public understood how to best store and handle food because the
majority of food poisoning cases occur in the home.  
</P>
</TEXT>
