<HEADLINE> Cameroun: 500 Secessionists Raid Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior divisional officer for
Mezam division of Northwest Province revealed for the first time
that about 500 assailants were involved in the attacks in the
province, local paper "Cameroun Tribune" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The revelation on the raiders in the Northwest Province was
made on Tuesday by Pierre Jill Mout Emgbang, the senior
divisional officer for Mezam while having an exclusive interview
with the paper.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Emgbang said the 500 youth from 15 to 25 years old were
trained by a secessionist movement named "Southern Cameroun
National Council" (SCNC), aimed at realizing the secession from
the nation's territory.
</P>
<P>
Till Tuesday, the disturbances in the six towns of the
province have caused three gendarme, seven assailants and three
civilians to die. Several arrests have been made. Strict security
measures have already been taken in the towns. The curfew is not
ended yet.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, situation in the last two days have
been relatively calm. People began to regain their usual
lifestyle. On Tuesday, the first official ceremony since
disturbances took place at the military base of the provincial
headquarters in Bamenda. It was the routine celebration that
usually marks the national military day. Eight military officers
received new epaulettes at the ceremony presided over by Governor
Fai Yengo Francis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
