<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Deepen Reform in Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China will further reform its
old-age pension system covering employees of city businesses,
making individuals shoulder a bigger part of the financial burden,
a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of the old-age pension contributed by the
individuals will be raised gradually in order to reduce the
financial burden of the state and the enterprises, Du Jian,
director of the social security department of the Ministry of
Finance, said at an international seminar on social security funds
management, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
To gradually increase individuals' share of contribution and
free the government and enterprises from social burdens they are
currently shouldering is a major aspect of the reform in China's
pension system in urban and township enterprises, according to Du.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprise employees should contribute a growing amount of
money to a basic pension fund, but no more than 20 percent of
their salaries," he said. "Meanwhile, enterprises' share shall be
reduced accordingly year by year."
</P>
<P>
Du said that China should set a reasonable standard of pension
benefits, adding that the basic pension benefit should be reduced
from 83 percent currently to around 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The basic benefit offered by the public-funded scheme shall be
about 20 percent of the average wages and the benefit from
individual accounts will be paid by installments according to the
accumulated amount in the accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other aspects of China's reform in the pension scheme for
enterprise employees include expanding the safety net of basic
pension to all enterprise employees in urban areas, as well as
self-employed workers, and keeping part of the surplus of pension
funds for benefits payment while investing the rest in treasury
bonds, Du revealed.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), China will
also promote the reform in unemployment insurance for enterprise
employees, expand the reform in the health insurance system,
improve the programs of social relief, social welfare and special
assistance, and establish and improve a social security fund
management system, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ian Rolland, chairman, president, and CEO of Lincoln National
Corporation of the United States, noted that the social security
reform has been made a common, worldwide issue by three universal
trends -- an aging population, declining birth rates, and a longer
life span partly due to significant advances in medical technology.
</P>
<P>
World Bank reports have shown that 500 million people were
above the age of 60 just seven years ago, about nine percent of
the then world population.
</P>
<P>
But by the year 2030, the World Bank estimates, the people of
that age group will reach 1.4 billion, about 18 percent of the
total population. Of the new growth, half will be in Asia and one
quarter in China.
</P>
<P>
As a big country, China's decisions and processes in social
security reforms will have far-reaching effects, not only
domestically but internationally, Rolland said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar was co-sponsored by the Ministry of
Finance and Lincoln National Corporation, and attended by
officials and experts from China, the World Bank, the United
States, Chile, Singapore, Canada, and some countries in East
Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
