<HEADLINE> No Shortcut to Normalize Pakistan-Indian Relations: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 2 (Xinhua) -- There is no shortcut to
normalize bilateral relations between Pakistan and India, a
Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We were looking for an integrated and structured approach
which would lead to the goal of cooperative and good neighborly
relations with India," he told a news conference when briefing
reporters on the Pakistan-Indian Foreign Secretary level talks
held in New Delhi late last month.
</P>
<P>
"For this, it is necessary to remove the root causes of tension
and anguish between the two countries," he said. "The centrality
of the Jammu and Kashmir issue in our relations should not be of
any doubt."
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman added that the very fact the Foreign
Secretary level talks resumed between Pakistan and India was a
"positive development".
</P>
<P>
"The round that has just been completed in New Delhi served to
clarify issues and we have come back to (the negotiating table)
with a better understanding of each other's point of view," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is wrong to believe there was any kind of breakdown in the
talks, (and) the dialogue between the two countries will
continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed hope that in the next session of
the Foreign Secretary talks Pakistan and India could "at least
agree on the agenda and mechanism for addressing all the
outstanding issues between the two countries meaningfully."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Foreign Secretary level talks aims to
prepare ground for meaningful talks between the two countries'
foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The New Delhi talks ended with no substantive progress, but
Pakistan and India agreed to continue their talks in Islamabad at
a date yet to be fixed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
