<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: African Stock Market Promising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chen Cailin)
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Leading African finance
makers are discussing the African stock market as the ongoing
sixth session of the conference of African ministers of finance
entered a second day here today.
</P>
<P>
A deep impression on the discussions is that developing
African stock market is full of vitality after its birth on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
To date Africa has 16 stock exchanges, most are less than 10
years old. Sub-Saharan markets are more recent, and eight of them
being established in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
These include Botswana (1989), Mauritius (1989), Ghana (1990),
Swaziland (1990), Namibia (1992), Zambia (1995) and Malawi
(1995).
</P>
<P>
However, these stock exchanges have great vitality because
they adapt to economic reforms and market economies of the
African countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the meeting, new markets are likely to emerge in
such countries as Uganda, Angola, Madagascar and Mozambique. A
regional exchange could also evolve in Cameroun for the central
Africa sub-region. The Abidjan Stock Exchange may assume a sub-
regional status to serve Francophone west Africa states.
</P>
<P>
African markets have made significant progress though they are
still young.
</P>
<P>
According to African ministers of finance, improvements have
been recorded in such indicators as market capitalization and
trading value, which grew by 73.58 and 152.78 respectively in the
five years ending 1995.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a number of African markets have continued to make
impressive price advances, falling within the top 10 best
performing markets in US Dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Cote d'Ivoire was the best performing global market.
Six of the best ten performing markets led by Kenya were African.
</P>
<P>
Interest in African markets is clearly rising as several
investment funds with focus on Africa have been estalished in the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
Among them are the African Investment Fund, Alliance Capital
(an American investment company), Robert Fleming (a British
merchant bank), and the Overseas Private Investment Corporation.
</P>
<P>
"That interest has been basically driven by reforms, growth in
some countries and the economic prospect of the region," said
Akamiokhor, director-general of the Nigerian Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
Of course, African markets have made positive developments,
but they are relatively small, illiquid, indeed at the
rudimentary stage of development.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, there are a total of 16 stock exchanges in Africa,
less than one-third of the number of African countries.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the total number of listings in African markets, at
under 2,000, is barely 10 percent and less than 5 percent of
emerging markets and world listings respectively.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and South Africa control 60 percent of listings. India,
with its 6,000 listed companies is three times of size of Africa.
These figures illustrate the fact that the limited number of
listings and the small size of the companies simply do not
provide enough choice for investors.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the meeting agreed that measures that governments could
take to hasten the maturity of African stock exchange markets
include strengthening the legal and regulatory framework,
establishing a proper institutional framework and training of
markets intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
Creating the environment for investment, both domestic and
foreign, is very crucial for the development of African
economies. This must also include an efficient capital markets in
which investors are protected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
