<HEADLINE> Tourism Creates Many Jobs for S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
estimates that the country's increased tourism has created
162,000 jobs directly and indirectly in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The local daily "The Citizen" quoted Tourism Minister Pallo
Jordan as saying that the number of overseas visitors to South
Africa increased by 1.26 million in 1995 compared with 1994, an
increase of 34.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the number was 465,158 visitors, or 10.2 percent more
than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said the higher number of tourists brought in an
estimated increase of 7.5 billion Rands (1.7 billion U.S.
Dollars) in 1995, which was a rise of 107 percent in foreign
exchange compared with 1994.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 increase over 1995 was 1.5 billion Rands (340 million
U.S. Dollars) or 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said it was assumed that one direct and two indirect
job opportunities were created by each 33 additional visitors.
</P>
<P>
According to an official statistics, in 1995, 24,000 direct
and 48,000 indirect job opportunities were created, and in 1996
the figures were 13,000 direct and 26,000 indirect job
opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
