<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Conservatives 14 Points Behind Labor, Poll Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) - Britain's ruling Conservatives
narrowed its gap with the opposition Labor Party in the latest
opinion polls to 14 points, the Guardian newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives climbed two points to 32 compared with last
month while Labor fell down two points to 46 points, according to
the Guardian/ICM poll, based on adjusted figures and taken over
the Easter weekend, just one month before voters go to the polling
stations on May 1.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that the latest sleaze crisis against the
Conservatives which dominated the past two weeks of electioneering
had not damaged the party as much as it originally feared, and
that strong economic figures were giving the party a boost.
</P>
<P>
But the finding also showed that public opinion wants the
Conservatives implicated in the "cash for questions" scandal to
quit as election candidates.
</P>
<P>
Asked by the pollsters whether Conservative MPs who have been
accused of taking cash for questions should stand as candidates in
the general election, an overwhelming 81 percent said they should
quit, with only 14 percent saying they should stand again.
</P>
<P>
Ten Conservative MPs are under investigation by a parliamentary
committee over allegations that they accepted undeclared cash in
exchange for asking questions in the House of Commons (lower
house).
</P>
<P>
So far, one Conservative MP implicated in the financial scandal
has resigned while two others quit their jobs in reaction to
accusations of involvement in sexual scandals.
</P>
<P>
When asked which of the party leaders would make the best prime
minister, 46 percent of the 1,200 pollsters chose Labor's Tony
Blair with Major on 32 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
