<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Pledges to Reinforce Co-operation with Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng said here today
that China will reinforce its co-operation with Canada in various
sectors with an effort to achieve further promotion of bilateral
relations in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy, Li expressed the hope that the two countries will be
respectful and beneficial to each other, with closer coordination
on international issues.
</P>
<P>
"China and Canada are both Pacific Rim nations of great
influence, and since the forging of diplomatic ties, especially
during recent years, bilateral ties have witnessed substantial
progress in various fields," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien has visited China twice,
and Li paid a visit to Canada in 1995. The exchange of visits
between leaders of the two countries have deepened mutual
understanding, and considerably accelerated the overall growth of
bilateral ties, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade co-operation between the two countries has
advanced with expanding fields, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the two sides signed the contract on joint
construction of the third phase of the Qinshan heavy water nuclear
reactor, which the premier cited as the mark of a new stage of
bilateral economic and technological co-operation.
</P>
<P>
China and Canada have become important co-operative partners in
economy and technology, and China will strengthen its co-operation
with Canada in various fields, and develop economic and trade ties
based on equality and mutual benefit, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Li said this conforms to the common interests of the two
countries. "We hope that the two countries will respect each
other, be mutually beneficial, increase their consultations, and
co-operate closer on international issues with a view towards
achieving greater promotion of bilateral ties in the next
century," Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy agreed with Li that relations between the two nations
have witnessed rapid growth over the recent years. Their
co-operation in economic, cultural, educational, science and other
sectors have reaped progress. Talks between leaders of the two
nations have also been fruitful, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Canada considers China an important country of the
Asia-Pacific region, and regards it important to advance its
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Canada is willing to reaffirm its friendly policy towards China
and continue its efforts for the expansion of communication and
co-operation in various fields, Axworthy said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
