<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Meets Essential Costs for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Students at the University of
Zimbabwe or those at any other tertiary institution have not been
asked to contribute towards their grants and loans but to meet
costs for their feeding and clothing during the year.
</P>
<P>
They would be expected to buy their own food and clothes and
provide money for entertainment while the government takes care
of their tuition, accommodation for those in halls of residence
and caution fees.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Higher Education Ministry Paul Mbambo told
yesterday the daily "The Herald" that no students will fail to
study at the University of Zimbabwe or any other institution as
the government is meeting all essential costs.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will disburse half of grant and loan
facility to institutions.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the students at the University of Zimbabwe held
their class boycott in protest against the government's new
fee-paying policy. Under the policy, the government pays 50
percent of the fees while students have to provide the other
half. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
