<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Sees Over 560,000 People Come, Leave in Easter Holidays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Between March 27 and 30, more than 260,000 passengers arrived
in Macao, while more than 300,000 people left, according to
figures released by local police departments.
</P>
<P>
Passengers flocked in from Hong Kong and China's mainland to
spend their holidays in Macao. Macao's airport, land pass
and sea ports were all crowded during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many Macao residents chose to spend their holidays
by traveling to Thailand, Taiwan and China's mainland. The number
of traveling groups was 50 percent up from the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Some air companies using Macao airport added additional
flights during the holidays. Air Macao, for instance, increased
two extra flights to Thailand and four extra flights to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
A major source of income for Macao, tourism is expected to see
a further five percent growth this year following a
five-percent-plus increase in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
