<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Moves to End Liberia's Crisis in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS), the broker of Liberian peace, made a
major go-ahead on Tuesday towards ending the crisis in the
induction of an independent electoral commission in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Disagreement over the chairmanship has twice delayed the
constitution of the commission, which has caused grave concern
from the international community over if Liberia's election can
be held on May 30 as scheduled with only about two months to go.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Chairman General Sani Abacha, who is also Nigeria's
head of state, has mandated Nigerian Foreign Affairs Minister Tom
Ikimi to go to Liberia to constitute an independent electoral
commission acceptable to both the Liberian people and the former
warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi left here for the war-ravaged country on Tuesday,
accompanied by Major-General Victor Malu, commander of the ECOWAS
peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Two candidates have been nominated for the chairman of
Liberia's electoral commission, each appointed, respectively, by
the ruling Council of State Chairperson Ruth Perry and former
warlord Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Last week, General Abacha asked the Liberian provisional
authorities to induct the commission on April 2 so as to ensure
general and presidential elections be held as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
It is against this background that Ikimi's tour to Liberia is
widely believed to be a mission to help the Liberians to meet the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement reached by ECOWAS heads of state in
Abuja, Nigeria last year, the electoral commission will comprise
ten members, including three aliens each from the United Nations,
the Organization of African Unity and the ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
A retired Nigerian diplomat has been appointed and left for
Liberia as representative of the ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
The other seven members will each come from three former major
warring factions, youth's organization, women's group, trade
union and the coalition of political parties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
