<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls on UN to Lift Embargo Immediately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has called on the United
Nations to honor its obligations to lift the sanctions on the
country immediately, claiming that the embargo has lost all
legitimate and legal reasons.
</P>
<P>
This came in a message sent by Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahaf to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, which was
carried in Iraqi newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
In the message, the Iraqi foreign minister asserted that the
embargo laid on Iraq is not based on the international law and
are contrary to the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining the embargo has become a revengeful policy
exercised by well-known quarters that seek to destroy a whole
people and deprive them of their right to live," al-Sahaf said
in his message, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi top diplomat reviewed all the grave effects of of
the U.N. embargo on the sanctions-stricken country, coupling
them with testimonies of the U.N. agencies, as well as those of
other international organizations and non-governmental bodies
about the deaths and the sufferings caused by the embargo to
Iraqis, the children in particular.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. specialized agencies announced that 4 million Iraqis,
most of them are children below five, "suffer much both
physically and mentally, from malnutrition and the deterioration
of health services," said the message.
</P>
<P>
"The UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund) has officially
announced that 4,500 Iraqi children aged below five die monthly
as a result of malnutrition, an acute shortage of medical and
laboratory instruments, and scarcity of medicines," the minister
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
