<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland Pushes For Early Handover of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government is pushing for
the early handover of Ferdinand Marcos' assets estimated to be
around 450 million U.S. dollars to the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
Jean Pascal Delamuraz, Swiss Public Economic Minister, said
here today that the Swiss government has filed a motion of appeal
with the Federal Court to find an immediate solution to the
problem that has troubled the two countries for almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
Delamuraz, who is heading a trade delegation for a three-day
visit to the country, said the Swiss government shared the same
view with Manila that a solution to the later Philippine
President's fund frozen in the Swiss Bank should be found "as
quick as possible".
</P>
<P>
"There are two fundamental realities which the Filipino people
should know, that we took the initiative at that time to freeze
the Marcos assets so that it would not go to just any claimants
and that the Swiss government has no interest in the money," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the judicial proceeding has already been
started in Switzerland and with the motion they filed, the Federal
Court will make a decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Delamuraz, however, added that the Federal Court is a distinct
and sovereign body and that the government has no means to press
it to make a decision favorable to the Philippine government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
