<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Cuts Army Recruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The recruits of the Mongolian
armed forces will be reduced by 30 percent this year, but the
recruits of border guards will increase by 10 percent, Lieutenant
General Damdinsuren, the chief of general staff, has announced.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was reported by the official newspaper
"Government News" on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Damdinsuren said the decision was taken in line with the policy
on reforming the armed forces system and establishing a
professional army.
</P>
<P>
The aim set by the government is to reinforce the border guards
and build up a professional, capable and highly mobilized army
which is small in number but highly trained.
</P>
<P>
The general said that the reduction of recruits will bring no
negative influence on the preparedness and capacity of the armed
forces since the defense expenditures will remain the same as
before.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has a total strengthen of 20,000 troops and its air
defense forces, communication troops and logistic troops have
already been professionalized.
</P>
<P>
Defense spending accounts for 4-6 percent of Mongolia's
national budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
