<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Canada Reaffirm Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China and Canada today reaffirmed
they will reinforce co-operation and promote bilateral relations
on the basis of mutual respect, mutual benefit, and seeking common
ground while reserving differences.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen this
morning held talks with visiting Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy, who is here on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Qian noted, Sino-Canadian relations
have maintained good development momentum with satisfactory
results achieved in various co-operative fields. Meanwhile, he
noted, frequent exchanges of high-level visits have played an
important role in the promotion of Sino-Canadian ties.
</P>
<P>
Since their economies are highly complementary, the two nations
have made steady and fast progress in their economic and trade
co-operation, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
In response, Axworthy said that the Canadian government has
always given priority to its relationship with China, adding that
Canada, satisfied with the progress in bilateral ties, hopes to
increase high-level contact to further promote mutually beneficial
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the issue of Hong Kong, Qian said the Chinese
government will unswervingly stick to the principles of "one
country, two systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong," and
a high degree of autonomy in Hong Kong and will implement the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
As of July 1, 1997, the Chinese government will grant exemption
of visas to those Canadian passport holders who make short-term
trips to Hong Kong, and specific arrangements will be made by the
HKSAR administration, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
China will resume sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1 this
year.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy said Canada is confident of Hong Kong's future, and
Canada's recent announcement regarding the exemption of visas to
HKSAR passport holders who undertake short-term travel to Canada
is a strong proof of the confidence.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that the mutually beneficial arrangements
made by both countries will be helpful for the reinforcement of
mutual trust, exchange of personnel, and expansion of economic and
trade co-operation.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also exchanged views on international
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Canadian Ambassador to China Howard Robert
Balloch, Chinese Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Co-operation Sun Zhenyu and Assistant Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi
signed, on behalf of their respective governments, two memoranda
on co-operative projects and an agreement on the purchase of real
estate for diplomatic uses. The two foreign ministers attended the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy arrived here Tuesday on his official visit to China as
Qian's guest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0113 </DOCNO>
