<HEADLINE> China's First Computer Contest for University Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China will hold its first computer
contest this month for university students using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Today's "China Youth Daily" quotes an official with the
All-China Students Federation as saying that students from at
least 32 universities will take part in the contest.
</P>
<P>
Students will be asked to send software designed by themselves
to the Organizing Committee by mid-June. Debates on hot topics
regarding information revolution will be conducted on the
Internet, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Only 100 students will be selected for the final round in
Beijing later this year, and winners will be given a computer as a
prize.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 100,000 Chinese using
the Internet, but that only a few families in major cities have
bought computers. A computer with the Pentium CPU costs almost
half the annual income of an ordinary family in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Some primary and high schools have opened computer
courses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
