<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel to Sign Land Transport Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Israel are planning to
ink a land transportation accord, local newspaper Daily News
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, due to be signed during Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy's official visit to Ankara, is aimed at easing the
transportation of passengers and goods between the two countries,
but no more details on the accord were reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord is expected to be implemented only when the
relations in the Middle East are "normalized," said the paper,
giving the fact that Syria lies between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli foreign minister will arrive in Ankara next
Tuesday for a two-day visit to Turkey in a bid to develop the
existing friendly ties between the two states.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the accord comes shortly after the Arab League
has called on its members to cease the normalization of their
relations with Israel and renew the economic boycott of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that the Turkish-Israeli agreement to be
concluded next week will draw strong response from Arab
countries, particularly Syria.
</P>
<P>
A military training agreement signed by Turkey and Israel in
February 1996 generated fear in Middle East countries that
Turkey was aligning itself with the Jewish state against Syria
and other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ankara has requested the Israeli government to
review its policy on the building of new settlements in East
Jerusalem which led to renewed clashes and violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
