<HEADLINE> Botswana, Mozambique Not to Prosecute Ex-S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Botswana and Mozambique have
made their stance clear that they would not prosecute former
South African soldiers who confess to having conducted the
cross-border raids during the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Botswana and Mozambican diplomats said on Tuesday in Pretoria
that their governments' approach towards the apartheid human
abuses would be to let bygones be bygones, a local daily "The
Citizen" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Botswana High Commissioner to South Africa, Oteng Tebape, said
while his government has not reached a final decision on the
matter, he did not foresee its calling for the extradition of
past perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
"This will have to come from individuals. It will not be a
government initiative," said Tebape.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mozambican Ambassador to Pretoria, Armando
Panguene, said his country has no intention of insisting on the
extradition of former South African soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Angolan military attache Andero Gonsalves also predicted his
government will "not be eager" to prosecute such soldiers, while
Zimbabwean Embassy official, Isaac Moyo, said his country will
address the issue once it arises.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said two former South African Defense Force
(SADF) chiefs were reportedly concerned that SADF members opting
to apply for amnesty ran the risk of extradition if they
confessed to having committed human right violations in
neighboring countries. 
</P>
