<HEADLINE> Tanzania Signs Globe Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has welcomed the
US-led world-wide science and education program co-ordinating the
work of students, teachers and scientists to study and understand
the global environment.
</P>
<P>
During a brief signing ceremony here on Tuesday, Tanzanian
Minister for Education and Culture Juma Kapuya said that the
program stands to increase people's awareness throughout the
world, adding that, "we will do our best to give this program a
chance to succeed".
</P>
<P>
US Ambassador to Tanzania Brady Anderson, signed the agreement
to adopt the program in Tanzania with Kapuya.
</P>
<P>
The program, initiated in 1995 by US Vice-President Al Gore,
is a world-wide network of primary and secondary school students
working under the guidance of teachers trained to conduct the
globe program.
</P>
<P>
Aims of the program include the enhancement of environmental
awareness of individuals world-wide to increase scientific
understanding of the earth and to improve student achievement in
science and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has become the 48th country to join the program which
officially began on the 25th Earth Day -- April 22, 1995.
</P>
<P>
It also becomes the sixth African country to sign the globe
agreement, after Benin, Chad, Gambia, Senegal and South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
