<HEADLINE> Palestinian Police Arrest 50 Islamic Jihad Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian police have
arrested 50 activists from the militant group Islamic Jihad,
which was believed to be behind at least one of the two suicide
bombings in Gaza Strip Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The arrests were made overnight in the Gaza Strip after
Tuesday's two bombings near the Netzarim Jewish settlement killed
two Palestinians and wounded five others. Islamic Jihad has
claimed responsibility for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian officials gave different versions of
the two incidents. Israel believed the two explosions to be both
suicide bombings which targeted Israeli school buses carrying the
settlers' children to school. Israeli security also said both
suicide bombers wore the uniforms of the Palestinian Preventive
Forces.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian side said the second explosion was caused
by Israeli soldiers who threw a grenade from their military jeep
at a Palestinian taxi, wounding five passengers in the car and
killing one Palestinian policeman riding on a nearby donkey cart.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified man called Israel Radio after the bombings to
claim responsibility for the two attacks in the name of the
militant Islamic Resistance Movement Hamas, but a Hamas spokesman
in Gaza strongly denied its organization's involvement. He said
the explosions were Israeli plots to create rifts between Hamas
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Later another man called Israel Radio to claim the bombings in
the name of Islamic Jihad, saying the suicide bombers came from
the Jabal Abu Ghneim Unit of the organization. Jabal Abu Ghneim is
the Arab name of Har Homa in southeastern Jerusalem, where Israel
is building a controversial settlement which sparked the latest
round of tension and violence.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the explosions, both sides traded accusations
over the responsibility for the attacks. Israel reiterated its
demand on the PNA to crack down on terrorism, while Palestinian
officials blamed Israel for creating the current tension that led
to the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's bombings came in the wake of the March 21 suicide
bombing in a Tel Aviv cafe which killed four people and wounded
dozens of others. Israel has since suspended peace talks with the
PNA and conditioned the resumption of the peace process on the
PNA's promise to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been put on high alert amid
intelligence warnings of more terror attacks since the Tel Aviv
bombing. Security experts believed that the two failed attacks
Tuesday would only increase efforts by Palestinian terrorist
groups to improve their image by staging successful
bombings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
