<HEADLINE> WNBF Rebels Surrender to Ugandan Authorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 rebels of the West
Nile Bank Front (WNBF) have surrendered or have been handed over
to the authorities in Arua District, north-western Uganda since
March 12, "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among the 415 WNBF rebels, 229 posed to be defeated Zairean
soldiers and surrendered to Zairean Banyamulenge rebels, and then
were handed over to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Some Zairean government troops fled to southern Sudan when
eastern Zairean towns of Ariwara, Ongbokolo and Kitambala fell
into the hands of the Zairean rebels.
</P>
<P>
Two other WNBF rebels were arrested when they passed
themselves off as refugees returning from Sudan last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
409 brigade of Uganda army had received 276 rifles from the
rebels so far.
</P>
<P>
Kambodia Mawa, a former WNBF officer, satisfied with the
conditions provided with by the Ugandan army. "We were not
whipped, slapped or denied food," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local media often referred to the lynch imposed by WNBF rebels
on their captives.
</P>
<P>
Security officers said they were bothered by the rooms of
jails and lack of enough food for expanding number of WNBF rebels
handed over to them.
</P>
<P>
"On average, we receive 20 WNBF rebels per day," said an
intelligence officer of 409 brigade in the north-western
district.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) has
still another 500 WNBF captives to be handed over to Ugandan
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The WNBF had lost its main forces in an ambush launched by the
SPLA in southern Sudan. Up to 800 WNBF rebels have been killed
and another hundreds have been captured in the operation. 
</P>
