<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Autonomy System Suited to China's Realities: Buhe (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Buhe stressed that the leadership of the Communist Party of
China is vital to the system of regional autonomy.
</P>
<P>
"Had it not been for the Chinese Communist Party, there would
not have been the emancipation of the Chinese people of all ethnic
groups, nor the equal, united relations of mutual help among the
ethnic groups," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Only by maintaining the unity of the motherland, can the
regional autonomy system be enforced, and the rights of equality
and autonomy be realized, and the rapid economic, social, and
cultural progress be made," Buhe added.
</P>
<P>
"In the meantime, only by rigorously enforcing this system,
could the equal rights and autonomy rights of ethnic minorities be
guaranteed, the initiatives of ethnic minority people be brought
into full play, and the national unity and common prosperity of
various minorities be better maintained and safeguarded," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
When asked about what should be done with respect to regional
autonomy work in the future, Buhe said that the system must
continue to improve, to consolidate and develop the harmonious
relations among all the ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Focus should be placed on legislations on ethnic affairs, and
efforts should be made to comprehensively enforce all the autonomy
policies with the help of law, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The 1984 Law on Regional Autonomy should be revised under the
new situation of building a socialist market economy, and relevant
supplementary legislation should be sped up, the senior lawmaker
said, stressing that "more importantly, supervision over the
compliance of laws on ethnic affairs must be intensified."
</P>
<P>
Buhe said that the Party and the government have paid great
attention to the development of ethnic minority groups, and have
adopted a series of preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
With joint efforts of all the Chinese people of all ethnic
groups to reform and open up, the economic gap between the areas
inhabited by ethnic minorities and prosperous coastal regions
generated by geographic, historical, and other reasons shall be
narrowed, Buhe said.
</P>
<P>
"And the coming century for all the Chinese people of all
ethnic groups will be brighter and better," he pledged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Autonomy System Suited to China's Realities: Buhe (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Fifty years of implementation of
the regional autonomy system has proved that it is suited to
China's real conditions and is completely correct, said a senior
Chinese official of ethnic mongolian group here today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Buhe, vice-chairman of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, said that,
under this system, "people of all ethnic groups are fully entitled
to the right to manage their own affairs and to have equally
participated in the state affairs."
</P>
<P>
"All are masters of the country," Buhe said.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region 50
years ago marked the start of this new system in China. Buhe used
to chairman of the regional government.
</P>
<P>
To date, there are five autonomous regions, 30 autonomous
prefectures, and 121 autonomous counties in the country. Of the
160 million population living in those autonomous areas, 45
percent are of ethnic minority groups.
</P>
<P>
Buhe said that under the unified leadership of the state,
regional autonomy has been implemented in all the areas where
ethnic minority people live in a compact community.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic minorities, accounting for 8.98 percent of the
country's total population, have 439, or 14.69 percent of deputies
to the NPC, China's top legislature. Even the minority with the
smallest population has its representative in the lawmaking body,
Buhe said.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, a great number of officials from the ethnic
minority groups have surged, according to the senior official, who
added that there are 2.4 million such people so far working for
the Party, government, legislative and judicial bodies
nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Workers on Strike in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan railway workers in
Nairobi, Nakuru, Mombasa and Kisumu went on strike on Tuesday to
demand their March salaries, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
In Nakuru, a town to the north of the capital Nairobi, more
than 1,500 workers of the Kenya Railways Corporation downed their
tools and staged a sit-in at the branch offices over their
delayed salaries.
</P>
<P>
Railway operations came to a standstill yesterday morning when
workers and staff converged outside their district headquarters
in Nakuru, demanding to be addressed by the District Manager,
Herman Kirika.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the workers, Branch Chairman of the Kenya Railways
Workers Union Peter Mumbe said that the retrenchment of more than
30 percent of the staff over the last two years has not made
things any better.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, the corporation had been delaying
in paying workers' salaries since April of last year and workers
have not been paid their March dues.
</P>
<P>
In Mombasa, a coastal city in the east of the country, some
500 railway workers gathered at the Mombasa Railway Station in
the morning and rejected an appeal by the management that they
continue working until Wednesday when their salaries are expected
to be paid.
</P>
<P>
Workers complained that they had been getting their salaries
late for the past three months.
</P>
<P>
In Kisumu, a town in the west of the country, 1,900 workers
downed their tools and staged a sit-in yesterday morning when the
corporation failed to pay them their March salaries.
</P>
<P>
The workers staged a peaceful sit-in outside the District
Traffic Superintendent's office.
</P>
<P>
In Nairobi, employees at the Central Workshop downed their
tools yesterday morning when they realized that they were not
going to be paid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
