<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Transplants African Tree To Negev Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli scientists are working
with African colleagues to acclimate the Zachum tree to the
Negev Desert in southern Israel, reported The Jerusalem Post
today.
</P>
<P>
The researchers of Ben-Gurion University believe that the
tree, which is native to Central Africa containing a high
percentage of edible oil, has great economic potential if
the transplantation is successful.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed at an international workshop on agricultural
development in arid regions organized by the university, which
is noted for its successes in desert economic research.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ze'ev Weisman said that the Zachum tree is valuable
because it produces chemical compounds that serve as a source
of hormones and steroids. He added that it was in ancient
times used for ritual and nutritional purposes and can be
used in the pharmaceutical industry in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The first plot of Zachum trees was planted this week at
Sde Teiman near Beersheba, a major city on the brink of the
Negev Desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
