<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to Counter Non-Tariff Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) are urged to find ways to counter
non-tariff barriers being introduced by some developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The issue was the spotlight at an ASEAN cooperation meeting in
Bangkok held here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some developed countries, like the United States, Japan and
Australia, are tending to use sanitary standards to block imports
of food from Asia, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has to find ways to ensure its exports of five major
agricultural products - frozen chicken, frozen prawns, tapioca,
canned tuna and pineapple - to retain the market, Petipong
Pungbun, deputy permanent secretary of the Thai Agriculture and
Cooperatives Ministry, was quoted as saying by the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members should join hands to voice their complaints at
the World Trade Organization on the non-tariff barrier issue,
according to Ajva Taulananda, chairman of the working group for
ASEAN agricultural goods promotion.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN brands should be established through improving the
quality of its food products, said Ajva, who is also a member of
the executive board of the Thai Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
He also urged ASEAN to set up an agency responsible for
standardization of agricultural product quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
