<HEADLINE> Shanghai To Reform Tourism Administration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is planning to establish
a new committee to manage tourism to develop a large unified
tourism system and for the city's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the organization will maintain authority over
the city's tourism-related sectors, including transport, municipal
construction, culture, business, trade, and customs.
</P>
<P>
It will be more powerful than the current Shanghai Municipal
Bureau of Tourism and is expected to be responsible for activities
that preserve or add to state-owned assets of the city's tourism
industry, and administration, guidance, and coordination of
tourism-oriented businesses in the city.
</P>
<P>
A new state-owned tourism assets share-holding company, a
tourism administrative office, and tourism industrial association
are also being proposed.
</P>
<P>
The city received 1.2 million overseas tourists and earned one
billion U.S. dollars from related services in 1996. It had 2.5
million domestic tourists and one billion yuan in profits from
them the same year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
