<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Strict Administration on College Enrollment in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China's top education body has
urged its colleges to detail their tuition costs when issuing
school admission plans in 1997, the first year of China's new
comprehensive system under which students pay for their own
education.
</P>
<P>
Colleges must not overcharge the students who are scheduled to
matriculate this autumn, an official from the State Education
Commission (SEC) said at a recent annual work meeting on college
enrollment in Taiyuan, the capital of central China's Shanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
No college has the right to refuse qualified applicants without
good cause; random application refusals have occurred in the past
in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Provincial college enrollment departments are entitled to act
on behalf of the violating colleges to accept new students, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Some professional training colleges will start to enroll new
students from polytechnic, vocational and technical schools, whose
mainstream graduates previously are not for higher learning.
</P>
<P>
But the students' majors in colleges should be suitable to
their professional training, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
The SEC also ruled that only art or sports-oriented schools can
organize independent enrollments in accordance with the SEC
regulations, the official said. The list of these particular
schools will be issued by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, more than 660 colleges among the country's
total 1,035 had adopted the self-pay system.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, all students recruits will pay their college tuition
-- one-fifth of their total expenses during college life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
