<HEADLINE> Central Bank Governor Vows To Open Finance Sector Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China will open its financial
sector wider to the outside world and tighten cooperation with
international financial organs, the central bank chief has said.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's bank of China, told a
group of Australian bankers Tuesday that China is expected to
achieve an international balance of payments and a stable currency
this year, thereby offering an attractive investment environment
to overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a ceremony marking the approval of a bank branch
license in Beijing to the Australia and New Zealand Banking Group
Ltd (ANG), the governor said, "The approval of the ANG Beijing
branch is another important step China has taken to open its
financial market to Australia."
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that six Australian banks have opened
ten representative offices and two branches in China, so far.
</P>
<P>
Dai hailed overseas financial institutions as a major force in
China's financial system, which had set up 158 operational
branches and 528 representative offices in China by the end of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total assets of China-based overseas financial
institutions hit 30 billion yuan last year, an increase of 56
percent from the previous year. 
</P>
