<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Control Risky Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand will apply
tougher standards to regulate finance and securities firms engaged
in venture-capital investments.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the new rules of the central bank are aimed
at keeping finance and securities businesses on safer ground by
discouraging risky lending.
</P>
<P>
A company providing venture capital will have to set aside
provisions for substandard assets if the venture fails to yield
dividends in its first year, according to a Bank of Thailand
official today.
</P>
<P>
If the performance of the venture declines relative to the net
worth of the company, then the finance and securities firm must
set aside more provisions, as providing venture capital is highly
risky, especially when the economy is slow.
</P>
<P>
The need for additional provisions will be a burden for finance
and securities firms and should thus deter them from engaging in
risky ventures, according to Vicharn Amornrojanapong, chief of the
bank examination and analysis department of the Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Problem loans on which interest is not being paid are now
classified as substandard assets. The new framework will set
stricter definitions.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, the loans of debtors who are able to pay
interest but their businesses lose money for three years will be
classified as substandard assets. The central bank is willing to
apply some leniency, examining details on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
Margin lending could be classified as substandard if customers
do not place promissory notes or cash as collateral.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will look into details of long-term
investments in ventures such as utilities or infrastructure firms,
since these typically do dot yield good returns for several years
initially.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Orders More Crackdown on Patent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has ordered state
agencies to step up crackdown on rampant patent violations to
prevent retaliation from the United States and the European Union
(EU).
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also approved requests that agencies responsible
for enforcement report their progress directly to the prime
minister every month, according to a government house press
release issued today.
</P>
<P>
At the cabinet meeting on Tuesday, the International Economic
Policy Committee, chaired by Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan,
reported that patent violations existed in the country and that
suppression had been ineffective.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve Thailand's image, the cabinet required the
Foreign Ministry and the Commerce Ministry to keep Thailand's
major trading partners, such as the US and the EU, informed of
crackdowns that Thailand takes against patent violators.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, US officials hinted that they were not
happy with Thailand's patent violation situation and that Thailand
might be moved from the watchlist back to the priority watchlist
in the US forthcoming annual review because of lack of efficient
measures and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
European Union officials will also visit Thailand to seek
information on violation of musical product patents in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the US government listed 46 countries (including
Thailand) and regions and four trading groups that maintain
"harmful trade barriers" against American firms, including
copyright and patent violations.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration will take 30 days to select specific
countries and regions from the list for further negotiations and
possible sanctions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition to Probe Fall of Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition, the
Nepali Congress (NC) party, has decided to find out what had
really led to the fall of the government under its party leader
Sher Bahadur Deuba last month.
</P>
<P>
A meeting held here Tuesday, the party's Central Working
Committee formed a three-member panel to investigate the very
reasons behind two NC MPs' absence from a lower house voting on
March 6.
</P>
<P>
The two MPs' absence directly led to the defeat of a confidence
vote for the NC-led coalition government in the 205-seat house.
</P>
<P>
The Deuba government resigned after it failed to prove majority
parliamentary support with only 101 lower house MPs voting in
favor, two votes short for the required majority to pass the
confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
The NC party Tuesday directed the newly-formed panel to submit
a report within 15 days in connection with the fall of the Deuba
government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports here said that Lokendra Bahadur Chand of the
National Democratic Party (RPP) managed to lure the two NC MPs
away from the house voting in order to bring down the Deuba
government.
</P>
<P>
Chand, a senior RPP leader, later formed a new three-party
government by forging a coalition with the Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) and a small party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
