<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish MPs Face Fines for Failing to Declare Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- One third Poland's members of
parliament are likely to be fined a month's pay for failing to
declare their personal financial and property interests within the
required deadline, the parliamentary news center told the press
today.
</P>
<P>
Under a law on the duties of parliamentarians approved last
year, lawmakers must register their financial interests including
bank savings, real estate, and shares in companies before
March 31 every year, and at the beginning and end of their
parliamentary life.
</P>
<P>
Personal economic activities and posts held in companies
also need to be declared.
</P>
<P>
The law bans members of parliament from using public property
to carry out business or financial activities, and from holding
top jobs in publicly quoted corporations.
</P>
<P>
Members who break the law or make false declarations will be
penalized and may face a prison sentence of up to five years, the
regulation says. Those who fail to declare in time will lose their
wages and subsidies for a month, which works out at 2,600 zloties
(about 867 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
