<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Province Active in Int'l Science Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has established relations with over 60 countries and regions and a
dozen international organizations for science research projects.
</P>
<P>
The projects cover a whole range of areas such as industry,
agriculture, forestry, biology, energy resources, environment,
geology, astronomy, and electronics.
</P>
<P>
The number of personnel involved in the projects is growing at
an annual rate of 20 percent. By the end of last year, six million
yuan had been spent on international programs. Most programs are
going well, according to Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
China's first high-energy gamma point source cosmic ray
observatory, a joint project with Hong Kong and the United States
in the provincial capital of Kunming, has prospects of becoming an
international observatory.
</P>
<P>
The study of the evolution of igneous rocks and tectonic magma
in Yunnan, which has complicated geological and geographic
conditions, has led to some interesting discoveries, as has
research in limnology in the limestone area of central Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake monitoring station, set up by a local research
body and the United States, and a monitoring station for
eletro-magnetic waves in earthquakes and volcanos, a joint effort
with Japan, have provided important technical data concerning
disasters.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the programs have practical value, sources
say, and have gotten strong backing from the United States, Japan,
Canada, New Zealand, Australia, France and some international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 local scientists involved in the programs have
introduced a number of their achievements to foreign countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
