<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thorough Probe Needed on Refugee Boat Disaster: Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Alberto Dini
and Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta today reiterated the need
for a thorough and transparent public inquiry into Friday's
sinking of an Albanian boat in the Adriatic in which more than 80
refugees were missing.
</P>
<P>
They told a joint session of the Senate foreign and defense
committees they hoped the inquiry would refute allegations that
the boat was rammed by an Italian naval vessel.
</P>
<P>
"There is unanimity in the government to make sure
that the verification of the facts is pursued with rigorous
criteria and with total transparency," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta told parliament that he had invited Albanian navy
experts to join investigations into the disaster and promised a
full and open inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Previous media reports and some Albanian survivors claimed the
refugee boat was deliberately rammed by Sibilla, an Italian navy
vessel.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister denied the allegations, saying that it was
still too early to speak about the cause of the sinking before it
was fully investigated.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta supplied a detailed reconstruction of the incident,
repeating the Italian navy's contention that the Sibilla
approached the Albanian boat slowly from behind after its repeated
attempts to contact the boat were ignored.
</P>
<P>
He said the Albanian boat then veered unexpectedly to one side
and hit the Sibilla before it began sinking.
</P>
<P>
But Andreatta denied the incident would affect Italy's aid
plans for Albania.
</P>
<P>
Air and sea reconnaissance operations continued today in
the area where the boat sank while patrols continued along
Albania's coast.
</P>
<P>
Albanian refugees have been pouring into Italy over the last
two weeks, fleeing from the unrest and violence that has gripped
the country since January when protests erupted over the collapse
of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands lost their life
savings.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council agreed on Friday to send a
Italian-led multinational protection force of about 5,000 troops
to Albania to protect emergency aid operations there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
