<HEADLINE> Italy to Continue Navy Patrol Despite Shipwreck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The sinking of an Albanian refugee
boat last Friday would neither stop the Italian navy patrol in the
Adriatic Sea, nor alter its plans to lead a multinational
protection force to the troubled Balkan country, the Italian
military sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta said he has asked his
Albanian counterpart Shaqir Vukaj to name a panel of experts to
investigate the accident with the Italian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Later today, the two defense ministers are expected to sign
final agreements reached last week between the two countries'
navies on patrolling the Otranto Channel and some technical
matters related to the patrol.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta dismissed the criticism that Italian navy ship
deliberately rammed the Albanian boat.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely shameful even to think that the Italian
vessel had the deliberate intention of ramming the Albanian boat,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Crowded with about 120 refugees, mostly women and children, the
Albanian vessel sank on Friday night after colliding with an
Italian navy ship, leaving four people dead and 83 others
missing. Only 34 people were rescued.
</P>
<P>
The accident put in doubts the Italian naval interdiction
patrols which began late last month after some 13,000 Albanians
flooded to Italian shore in an uncontrolled exodus from their
chaotic homeland.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta and Vukaj will also discuss the international
protection force (IPF) to be sent to Albania.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the 5,000-strong IPF will be Italians, while
France, Spain, Greece, Austria, Turkey, Romania, Hungary and
Slovenia have also promised to contribute.
</P>
<P>
The IPF has been given green light by the United Nations
Security Council and has the blessing from the European Union and
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Italian General Luciano Forlani, currently commander of the
third armored corps base in Milan, will be the commander of the
IPF.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials from the contributing nations are scheduled
to have a meeting in Rome Wednesday, which will also be attended
by Vukaj.
</P>
<P>
However, Italy's policy of military intervention has aroused
criticisms from within the government majority alliance.
</P>
<P>
Fausto Bertinotti, leader of the Communist Refoundation Party
which gave Prime Minister Romano Prodi's government its majority
in the Lower House, said the mission "would only aggravate the
Albanian situation" and would expose Italian soldiers to danger.
</P>
<P>
Green party's Luigi Manconi contested the navy patrols, saying
he would fight "until the government changes its mistaken and
irresponsible position which has caused and will continue to cause
suffering." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
