<HEADLINE> Home of Terracotta Warriors Attracting Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Xi'an, the capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, has been popular with overseas tourists
because of its terracotta warriors, but the city is attracting
many foreigners now for a more modern reason.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an Hi-tech Industry Zone now has 268 overseas-funded
enterprises, with 510 million US dollars in overseas funds. The
zone in the city's suburbs reported a total income of 7.58 billion
yuan in 1996, up 66 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
As one of the major science research and education bases in
China, Xi'an has hundreds of research developments and patents
annually and has become a center of overseas investment in
northwest China, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Since the industrial zone was approved as a national level
industrial development area in March 1991, local authorities have
spent more than four billion yuan on infrastructure, and have
improved the investment environment to meet market economy demands.
</P>
<P>
Investors from more than 20 countries and regions, including
the Untied States, Japan, Germany, the Netherlands, the Republic
of Korea, Hong Kong, and Taiwan, have settled in the hi-tech
industry zone. And thanks to the infusion of funds and technology,
hi-tech industries have become a backbone of the zone, in
electronic information technology, bio-pharmaceutical engineering,
energy saving techniques, and new materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
