<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Washington Spat Over Pork Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States is seeking
compensation from the Philippines for the country's refusal to
open its market to American pork and poultry products, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Philippine Trade and Industry Secretary
Cesar Bautista as saying that negotiations could prevent a
full-blown trade dispute between the two countries, which have
just recently resolved a tiff on Philippine garments exports to
the US.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said his department is open for negotiations with the
U.S. Trade Representative on a "compensation package" but the
form, either in cash or in another product, will be decided by the
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero said recently that
there is no trade barrier but that Filipinos do not like the taste
of frozen pork.
</P>
<P>
However, the US alleged that the Philippine government's
allocation system for pork imports has unduly favored local pork
producers since they are the ones given the allocations to import
and are therefore likely to protect their market by not importing.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines should start opening its pork and poultry
market to American imports in 1995 but it only began to do so in
1996 with small trade volumes.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreement last month to expand
Manila's garments exports quota after it filed a suit before the
World Trade Organization, protesting Washington's new
country-of-origin rules on textile and apparel imports.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. provision which took effect last July stipulated
that home furnishings and made-up textile goods would not be
considered Philippine made unless the raw materials were locally
sourced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
