<HEADLINE> NAM Still Relevant in Post Cold War Era: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) was
still needed by the international community in the post cold war
era, said Nana S. Sutresna, head of the NAM Executive Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian ambassador-at-large said Tuesday in Padang, West
Sumatra province, that Indonesia will continue to support NAM,
despite criticism that the organization is out-of-date and
ineffective in dealing with international problems, especially the
Arab-Israeli dispute, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there is little NAM can do to help resolve the
Arab-Israeli conflict, but said that all NAM members support
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign loans and economic problems faced by developing
countries indicated that NAM programs which prioritize economic
development in developing countries ... are still needed in order
to cope with the world's poverty problems," he added.
</P>
<P>
The acceptance of NAM as an international organization can not
be seen apart from Indonesia's role in making various adjustments
to the progress of time, he said.
</P>
<P>
During its chairmanship from 1992 to 1995, Indonesia had
consistently striven to solve the foreign debt problems that
burdened NAM members, Sutresna noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
