<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Yugoslavia Refugees Call for Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting to solicit aid
for refugees from regions of the former Yugoslavia ended here on
Tuesday. The meeting appealed to international humanitarian
organizations not to reduce aid to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Participants expressed concern about the present situation of
the refugees and urged the international community to create
necessary conditions for them to return home.
</P>
<P>
About 250 representatives of overseas Yugoslav communities in
15 countries, including Europe, the United States, Canada and
Australia, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, civil wars in the former Yugoslavia
region, especially in Bosnia, about two million people were forced
to leave their homes. At present, about 700,000 people are staying
in Yugoslavia, and the rest scattered in the United States and
other European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
