<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Vows to Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
expressed the hope that poverty will be eliminated by the end of
the seventh five-year development plan in 2004.
</P>
<P>
"Fighting poverty is the most important means of overcoming the
social gap," said the president in a written statement read out by
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas in Dili, East Timor on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the total number of those living in
poverty was on the decline, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, data showed those living below the poverty line
reached 25.9 million or 13.7 percent of the total 200 million
Indonesian population. By 1996, this figure had fallen to 22.5
million or 11.3 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
"We are still trying to reduce the incidence of poverty through
the use of presidential decrees for the under-developed village
program (IDT)," said Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian economy grew by 7.82 percent in 1996. "This
growth, although below that of the previous year (8.2 percent), is
still high enough when compared to the projected annual growth of
7.1 percent," the president pointed out.
</P>
<P>
With the 7.82 percent growth rate, the income per capita
managed to increase from 1,039 US dollars in 1995 to 1,140 dollars
in 1996, Soeharto added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
