<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Bank Busy in Looking for New Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Four of the eight overseas banks
in Shanghai that have approval to deal in local currency have
settled in the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
The relocation in east Shanghai was a requirement for doing
yuan business of the central bank. CitiBank, the Hong Kong and
Shanghai Banking Corporation Ltd, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
and the Industrial Bank of Japan have moved their local branches
to the development zone.
</P>
<P>
The other four -- Standard Chartered Bank, the International
Bank of Paris and Shanghai, and Japan's Daiichi Kangyo Bank and
Sanwa bank -- are looking for new homes across the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
China's opening up of the yuan business to overseas bank
branches is still at an experimental stage, and approved banks can
handle deposits, make loans, conduct settlements, providing
guarantees, and invest in government and other bonds.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of all the restrictions on the overseas bank branches
in dealing with the yuan-based business, we still hail it a
significant step that China has taken to open-up its financial
sector," said a foreign financier in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
