<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province to Invest in Industrial Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province will spend 61.2 billion yuan on state-owned enterprises
by the year 2000 to reshape the industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
The governor, Tian Fengshan, says that it is a strategic move
to improve the state economy. Heilongjiang used to be one of the
main industrial production bases of China, but has been mired down
by poor economic performance by many state-owned enterprises for
years.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the money will be spent on technology, know-how, and
equipment to help adjust the industrial structure of the local
economy," Tian said.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial plan, priority will be given to
automobile, electronics, petrochemical, pharmaceutical, and food
processing industries, which are expected to become pillar
sectors of the local economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The province will try to make high-tech industrial output value
contribute four percent of the province's total, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the province will take steps to make it a
production base of equipment for power plants, construction
materials, tires, and forestry products.
</P>
<P>
To help realize the plan, the province will open further to
overseas investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
