<HEADLINE> Albania, Greece Seek Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Stability in Albania is in the
interests of the Balkan region and Greece, a senior Greek official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Aleksander Filo, secretary general of the Greek Foreign
Ministry, who arrived in Tirana today for a two-day visit, said
his country is preparing to join the U.N.-approved multinational
force which will go to Albania to protect humanitarian relief
operations and help the country restore order. Greece, which
shares its northern border with Albania, is sending a battalion to
participate the multinational army.
</P>
<P>
Filo's visit, the third by Greek officials since Albania was
rocked by unrest last month, is seen as a move to help Albania
overcome its current troubles and to strengthen cooperation
between the two countries based on established mutual
understanding.
</P>
<P>
Today Filo met Albanian President Sali Berisha, Prime
Minister Bashkim Fino and other ministers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last Friday authorized the dispatch
of a 2,500-strong European-dominated multinational force led by
Italy to Albania for three months to carry out relief operations.
</P>
<P>
Albania has repeatedly asked for foreign military assistance
since massive protests, sparked by the collapse of pyramid savings
schemes, turned into armed revolt earlier March. More than 150
people have been killed in the violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
