<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Obliterates Moscow's Monument to Last Tsar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A bomb destroyed Moscow's only
monument to Russia's last tsar, Nicholas II, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin denounced the bombing
as a senseless act.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that people can have different comments on
Nicholas II himself, but the brutal behavior (the bomber's) can
never wipe out a country's history. He believed that the police
would make every effort to search for the bomber.
</P>
<P>
The 10-meter bronze statue, completed last May by a Russian
artist, was blown to pieces at about 6.30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Police were still gathering the pieces in late afternoon,
though at first they treated the alert as an April Fool's joke.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas was overthrown 80 years ago when the Bolsheviks took
power.
</P>
<P>
But with the collapse of the former Soviet Union, public
attention began to transfer to the monarchy. Even the resurgent
Orthodox Church is considering making Nicholas a saint. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
