<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The U.S. PPG Industries Group announced a 100
million dollar investment to build a dye and resin factory in
Brazil, the group's first factory in Brazil and its second in
South America.
</P>
<P>
The factory will be built in the state of Sao Paulo in
southeastern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The PPG Industries Group has 96 factories in 15 countries,
which earn an annual profit of nearly seven billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The first market for swaps in Chile began operation
on Tuesday and the establishment is defined by its managers as a
new way for companies to exchange products and services.
</P>
<P>
Jaime Montero, the general manager of the market, said it will
reduce costs for companies and, in Chile, has the potential to
make close to 200 million U.S. dollars worth of transactions.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- A total of 548 new in-bond assembly
(maquiladora) companies was established between the ends of 1995
and 1996 in Mexico, representing an increase of 18 percent, said
the Commerce and Industrial Promotion Ministry (SECOFI).
</P>
<P>
These new establishments and expansions had created more than
90,900 jobs. Up to December 1996, the maquiladora sector employed
more than 880,000 workers, said a SECOFI report.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua signed the international coffee agreement
last Thursday, increasing the number of signatories of this pact
between coffee growers and consumers to 62, Celsius Lodder, the
executive director of the International Coffee Organization (ICO),
announced.
</P>
<P>
According to the ICO, which is based in London, the exporter
members who signed the agreement are responsible for 95 percent of
world coffee exports. Nicaragua exported around 900,000 sacks of
coffee in the 1995-96 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
