<HEADLINE> GLOBE Program Begun in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A program aimed at helping young
people and children become more aware of the environment has been
started in Tibet, one of the highest inhabited areas in the world.
</P>
<P>
Students involved in the program will collect data on
temperatures, rainfall, clouds, soil moisture content, and
biology, all of which will be fed into the Internet for the US's
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration operations in the
state of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, the students will also learn more about the global
environment and become more aware of the environmental crisis they
are facing.
</P>
<P>
The "Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the
Environment" (GLOBE) program was launched by US Vice-President Al
Gore on April 22, 1994, the World Earth Day, and is an
international cooperative project for environmental education.
</P>
<P>
An experimental high school affiliated with Beijing Normal
University and three other Chinese schools joined the program in
1996 after China and the US signed a cooperative agreement on the
project.
</P>
<P>
Gore said that it was "very impressive" when he visited the
experimental high school last week and joined students in
collecting and processing data.  
</P>
</TEXT>
