<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: British Election Campaign in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Just one month away from the
general election, the candidates of the two major parties in
Britain are gearing up their efforts to become the host of No. 10
Downing Street in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major, whose Conservative Party was behind
the opposition Labor Party by 20 percentage points in opinion
polls, set off for north London this morning, trying to shake off
the sex and financial scandals that had dominated the first
two-week campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Three Conservative officials resigned last week over
allegations of personal impropriety or involvement in a
cash-for-question row in parliament. Two more Conservative MPs,
allegedly involved in sexual and financial scandals, are under
strong pressure from other party members to quit.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is booming, and what we have to do is to make sure
nobody changes it," Major told a crowd of people in a Croydon DIY
store.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Labor Party leader Tony Blair also set off today on
a pre-election tour to woo the crucial middle-class floating
voters. Apparently, both parties, eager to move back to daily
issues such as education and economy from the sleazy scandals,
regarded today as the formal start of their campaigns for the
election. The past two weeks of electioneering was dominated by
dirty scuffles of the two parties and kept in low key.
</P>
<P>
"I feel the responsibility... But there is also a sense of
excitement, of what we can achieve, of what we can do. The whole
of my political life has been a preparation, if you like, for this
period of time," 43-year-old Blair told reporters on his way to
Northampton in central England, the first stop of the nation-wide
meet-the-people tour.
</P>
<P>
"Judge our policies on what they are, not on what the Tories
(Conservatives) say they are. Our policies are mainstream, costed,
sensible, better for Britain," Blair told a news conference before
boarding his "battle bus" that will take him to 60 towns and
cities.
</P>
<P>
Labor has gained great advantages out of the sleazy issue,
claiming it underlined the need for a change in British politics
and the fact Conservatives had been warped by holding power for so
long. The Conservatives has ruled Britain over the past 18 years
since Margaret Thatcher beat the Labor in 1979 election.
</P>
<P>
Major's poorly-started campaign got a boost today from
Thatcher, who launched a vigorous attack on Blair and the
"boneless wonder" of the new Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
"The whole of Mr Blair's strategy in creating the boneless
wonder that calls itself New Labor is to reassure the electorate
in its illusion. But illusion it remains," Thatcher said in an
article which was published in today's Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
Countering the attack, Blair, who is bidding to become UK's
youngest prime minister of this century, urged the voters to put
their trust in his party. "Be strong, be of good courage, put your
trust in us and we will repay that trust 1,000 times over in the
years ahead."
</P>
<P>
In another attempt to win over the voters who seems more
favorite for the Labor, Major said today he remained ready to hold
a television election debate with Blair.
</P>
<P>
The televised debate, which would be the first in British
electoral history if held later this month, now seems running to a
dead end after the two parties disputed over the format of the
debate. Both charge the other side for responsibility.
</P>
<P>
"We the Conservative Party have accepted the terms of the
broadcasters' proposals as they stand even though they are not
perfect from out point of view," he told a campaign news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts believe Major has nothing to lose from the
debate while Blair has little to win. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
