<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Construction spending in the
U.S. increased sharply by 2.3 percent in February, the biggest
gain in 11 months, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that spending on residential,
non-residential and government construction totaled 603.8 billion
dollars in the month at a seasonally adjusted annual rate.
</P>
<P>
The gain of the U.S. construction spending in February was led
by an increase of 4.1 percent in public spending, the strongest
since last September. Residential spending advanced by 1.2 percent
with single-family construction gaining 1.5 percent. The spending
on non-residential construction increased by 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the spending in January was down by 0.3
percent other than 0.4 percent announced one month ago.
</P>
<P>
It was the latest in a string of stronger-than-expected
government economic reports.
</P>
<P>
The latest economic reports have led analysts to believe that
the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) will further raise the short-term
interest rate this year to curb inflation.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the tightening of U.S. monetary policy,
along with increases in long-term rates set in markets, should
eventually put a damper on the highly rate-sensitive construction
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
