<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians Exchange Accusations Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
officials exchanged accusations over responsibility for the two
suicide bombings in the Gaza Strip today.
</P>
<P>
Two Palestinian suicide bombers prematurely blew themselves up
early this morning in two separate spots near a Jewish
settlement, but both missed their targets and caused no Israeli
casualty. In the second explosion, a Palestinian taxis was
damaged and five Palestinian passengers inside the car were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
A man who claimed to belong to the militant Islamic Resistance
Movement Hamas later made an anonymous call to Israel Radio's
Arabic Service to claim responsibility, but a Hamas spokesman in
Gaza denied the organization's involvement and held Israeli
agents responsible for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government immediately blamed the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) for failing to prevent the attacks, which
it alleged were targeting the buses carrying Israeli children to
their school.
</P>
<P>
"This is a return to the most heinous kind of crimes which
inflicted the peace process from its beginning. Unless the
Palestinian National Authority does something about this, or
unless they clamp down on terrorism, the peace process is in real
danger," said Bar Illan, media adviser to Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the explosions, Netanyahu convened a urgent
meeting of the security establishment to discuss the
situation. Netanyahu said the latest attacks showed that the PNA
was not doing enough to crack down on terrorism, a condition set
by the Israeli prime minister on reviving the deadlocked peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak disclosed that one of
the suicide bombers wore the uniform of Palestinian security
forces. He said that the incidents underscored the importance
of the security cooperation between the two sides in fighting
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials rejected Israel's accusation of the PNA's
failure to prevent the attacks. PNA Secretary Tayeb Abdel Rahman
blamed Israeli soldiers for throwing explosives at the Palestinian
taxis in the second alleged suicide bombing. PNA President Yasser
Arafat also accused Israel of being responsible for the second
explosion.
</P>
<P>
Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat held the Israeli
government responsible for creating the current tension which
pushed the peace process into a "major crisis." He said the
Netanyahu government was escalating the situation with continued
unilateral decisions and settlement expansions.
</P>
<P>
The current tension was triggered by Israel's decision to
build a settlement in East Jerusalem on March 18. Stone-throwing
Palestinian protesters have been clashing with Israeli soldiers
across the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Two more Palestinians, including a Palestinian policeman taking
part in demonstrations, were killed by Israeli soldiers on the
West Bank today, bringing to three the Palestinian death toll
in the latest round of violence.
</P>
<P>
Today's bombings came in the wake of the Hamas suicide bombing
in central Tel Aviv on March 21, which killed three Israeli women
and the bomber and wounded dozens of others. Israel has since
suspended peace talks with the PNA in order to pressure the
latter to launch a long-term crackdown on terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
