<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Finance Ministers Discuss Challenges of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Participants of the Sixth
Session of the Conference of African Ministers of Finance
discussed here today the issue of challenges of the African debt
problem.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, leading African finance policy makers,
including ministers of finance and central bank governors,
reviewed the issue of the African debt problem. Their discussions
were centered on the debt initiative for heavily indebted poor
countries (HIPCS), launched by the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The initiative targets 41 of the world's most highly indebted
countries, 33 of which are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The debt situation in Africa seriously impedes the continent's
development, they said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of fianance were particularly vocal on the
question of debt-to-export ratios, arguing that their commodity
exports were dominated by multinationals to whom accrued a large
proportion of export earnings. The World Bank and the IMF should
therefore desist from considering the market value of exports in
their calculations, they said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's debt is now estimated at more than 340 billion dollars,
while the debt servicing payments amount to 24 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Present at today's meeting were Executive Secretary of the
United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) K. Y. Amoako,
Uganda's Finance and Economic Planning Minsiter J.
Mayanja-Nkangi, World Bank Vice-President Jean-Louis Sarbib,
African Development Bank Vice-President Ferhat Lounes, and IMF
Deputy Director A. Basu.
</P>
<P>
The three-day session, which opened here Monday, will be
closed tomorrow afternoon. enditem

