<HEADLINE> Egypt Rejects Israeli Charge of Formenting Arab Anger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today rejected Israel's harsh
accusation that it has instigated other Arab countries to take a
tough line against the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Israel's decision to
begin construction of a Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem is
to blame for the current peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli measures were behind the Arab League's resolution
calling for a freeze in relations with Israel and reactivation of
the Arab economic boycott of Israel," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He brushed away Israel's criticisms of Egypt for urging Arab
parties to halt normalization steps with Israel and bring back the
economic boycott as a mere publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
"These are attempts to evade the responsibility and will never
influence Egypt's stance," he emphasized, adding that Egypt will
not comment on "such diatribes."
</P>
<P>
He urged Israel to immediately reverse the decision this month
to go ahead with a 6,500-unit Jewish settlement at Jabal Abu
Ghneim or Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We have to save Jerusalem from all measures that would change
its position and preempt serious negotiations on its status," he
said. "The resolution on Jerusalem approved by the Arab League
Council meeting Monday has carved out such a clear Arab stance,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs have decided to stop normal relations, revive
economic boycott, close down Israeli missions and withdraw from
Mideast multilateral talks, in the strongest concerted step they
have taken since the hardline Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu took office last year.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accused Israel of sabotaging the peace
process by building a Jewish housing project on disputed land in
East Jerusalem where they want to establish a capital.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Netanyahu's description of the resolution as
"political or diplomatic violence" indicated that his assessment
of the regional situation is "wanting and incomplete."
</P>
<P>
"Salvaging true peace, rather than a lame peace which is meant
to serve interests of one country, has always been our objective,"
said the top Egyptian diplomat.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of mounting tension between the two countries,
Netanyahu heaped harsh criticism on Egypt today, accusing it of
double-dealing and inciting the Arab world to gang up on Israel.
</P>
<P>
"To my regret, Egypt is playing a leading role in the
incitement of the Arab world, in the political struggle the Arabs
are waging against us and not just from today," he told Israel
Radio.
</P>
<P>
However, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, in an interview with
an Israeli newspaper, called the Har Homa housing plan as "the
most dangerous thing conceivable" that has sparked a new round of
violence, including West Bank stone throwing riots and suicide
bombings by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the project continues, no one will be able to
contain the festering situation any more. "Why do you add oil to
the fire?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
