<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Failure Rate in UK Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of business collapsing
in Britain dropped by nearly 10 percent in the first three months
of this year, according to Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, the business
information group, today.
</P>
<P>
Philip Mellor, senior analyst at the group, said: "We had
feared that an increase in company liquidations might bring a host
of smaller firm bankruptcies in its wake.
</P>
<P>
"This has not happened yet. But, with the business climate
being so competitive, it remains to be seen if the decline in
business failures continues throughout the year."
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the number of business
failures including companies, partnerships and sole traders was
10,329, 1,101 fewer than in the first three months last year.
</P>
<P>
The drop was caused mainly by a 13.7 percent reduction in the
number of larger companies going into liquidation, Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet said.
</P>
<P>
However, the drop in business failures is spread unevenly, with
every region having a decline except the West Midlands (27.4
percent) and Scotland (25.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
The number of business failures in London was barely changed:
1,714 failed in the first quarter of 1997 against 1,789 in the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Dun &AMP; Bradstreet also said, the number of liquidated companies
fell from 5,237 in the first quarter of last year to 4,517 this
year.
</P>
<P>
The number of bankruptcies among smaller businesses fell 6.1
percent in the same period, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
