<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Growth to Slow Down in Kenya: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said today that Kenya might register a decline in economic growth
and a possible increase in the rate of inflation this year.
</P>
<P>
Opening the sixth session of the seventh parliament here this
afternoon, Moi noted that his government was compelled to divert
resources from other projects to cope with the just-ended
drought.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the management of natural disasters put a
considerable strain on the available resources although it was
necessary to facilitate speedy mobilization of resources to the
affected people.
</P>
<P>
However, Moi told members of parliament that famine relief was
a temporary measure and there was need to develop the
anti-natural disaster capacity of people in drought-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
He urged the members to focus more on the real issues facing the
country aimed at improving the well-being of the Kenyan people
and to set aside narrow sectarian interests.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that the current famine facing the Kenyan people due
to the prolonged drought in most parts of the country is an issue
which transcended narrow sectarian interests.
</P>
<P>
Kenya had experienced a prolonged drought since the second
half of last year and the government early this year declared it
a nationwide disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has decided to allocate about 110
million U.S. Dollars to import relief food to feed some 2.5
million people affected by the drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
