<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Try to Get Free from UN Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has mapped out
plans to ensure the country is not censured at the current
session of the U.N. Human Rights Commission in Geneva, a
presidency source said today.
</P>
<P>
The plans are in the light of the recent aborted trip of the
U.N. Human Rights Commission rapporteurs that might draw calls
for punitive actions against Nigeria, the source said.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken necessary steps to check any harsh resolution
against us during the current session of the commission," the
source was quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, the government will show at the
session the extent to which Nigeria has gone for cooperation with
the rapporteurs.
</P>
<P>
The information to be made available would guide the delegates
attending the session in arriving at any decision on Nigeria, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is not worse than what it was last year," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been under the fire of the West for its alleged
poor human rights record, particularly following the execution of
nine minority nationality activists in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, the United States and Canada have since
imposed sanctions against the western African country, while the
Commonwealth has suspended its membership for two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
