<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BBC-Discovery Joint Venture Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The BBC's 500 million-plus US
dollars joint venture with Discovery Communications of America
will not start before June -- six months later than forecast --
delaying the launch of new international channels until early next
year.
</P>
<P>
The Times today quoted BBC sources as saying that "more time
was needed because the venture had become much broader and more
complex than originally expected".
</P>
<P>
In September, when the two sides revealed they were in talks,
they said they hoped to reach final agreement by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deal is designed to build up the corporation's commercial
income by exploiting the BBC name in overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
It will do so by creating new subscription-TV channels that
will be shown on satellite and cable systems and through joint
program developments.
</P>
<P>
The venture with Discovery will be similar in concept to the
one formed two weeks ago with Flextech, the cable and satellite
programer that is ultimately controlled by Tele-Communications Inc
(TCI), America's beggest cable company.
</P>
<P>
The BBC-Flextech joint venture gained exclusive UK and Irish
rights to much of the BBC's programming archives and will invest
about 224 million US dollars to launch eight channels in the
Autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
