<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Steel Giants Merger Takes Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A merger between Germany's two
biggest steel concern -- Thyssen and Krupp-Hoesch went into effect
today, resulting in the world fifth-biggest steekmaker with an
estimated annual production of 15 million tons of steel.
</P>
<P>
Plagued by overcapacity at home and cheaper imports from
eastern Europe and Asia, the two companies agreed last week to
merge their steel operations up from April 1. The accord has
already been approved by the supervisory board of Thyssen, and an
endorsement by its Krupp counterpart, due in May, is believed to
be a sheer formality.
</P>
<P>
The merger was prompted by Krupp's announcement of a hostile
takeover bid for its larger rival Thyssen last month. After mass
labour protests and strikes, as well as political uproar, Krupp
dropped its hostile takeover plans on March 19 when it became
clear that the two were prepared to merge on friendly terms.
</P>
<P>
Under the merger accord, Thyssen will hold a controlling 60
percent stake in the merged entity, called Thyssen Krupp Stahl AG.
Thyssen's chief executive, Ekkehard Schulz, will assume its top
management post.
</P>
<P>
About 6,600 jobs will be phased out in the coming five years
due to the incorporation and annual cost-savings of about 550
million German marks (about 329 million U.S. dollars) are expected
to be achieved from the year 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
