<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Economy to Sustain Further Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The economy of Ireland is set to
remain the strongest in the European Union (EU), with a further
growth of 6 percent in 1997, according to the latest Bank of
Ireland poll.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the survey suggest that low interest rates
combined with improving economic conditions internationally will
underpin sustained growth in the Irish economy throughout the rest
of this year, press reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
Some 77 percent of Irish business leaders expected to report
increased turnover in the current year, with 65 percent basing
their expectations on continued growth in the country's economy
over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which reflects the views of 178 senior Irish
executives in various sectors of the economy, shows that 43
percent of companies are planning to recruit additional staff.
</P>
<P>
Jim Powell, Bank of Ireland's chief economist, was quoted as
saying that the results were consistent with further evidence from
various sectors of the Irish economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite clear that the economy is enjoying another very
good year and growth of 6 percent is easily achievable. The level
of confidence reflects the very benign interest rate situation and
also the improvement in external economic conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
In overall terms, the survey pointed to a very optimistic
picture for the Irish economy this year, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
