<HEADLINE> Germany's New Anti-Terror Special Unit Enters Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Germany's new special military unit,
known as the Kommandos Spezialkraefte (KSK), officially entered
service today, ready for worldwide deployment to deal with
emergencies such as hostage crises and terrorist attacks, the
German Defense Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The first 20 KSK soldiers, out of a planned group of 960, have
become fully operational at their headquarters in the southwestern
German city of Calw. The full unit is due to be completed by the
year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The main mission of the KSK is to free hostages but they are
also expected to obtain "crucial information" from international
crisis or conflict areas as well as to counter "subversive
forces."
</P>
<P>
Soldiers applying for joining the elite unit are subject to
tough entry tests. Their maximum age is limited to 38.
</P>
<P>
The new unit, which is under the command of the German armed
forces Bundeswehr, will run parallel with another special unit,
called GSG 9 run by the German Bundesgrenzschutz border police.
The latter is allowed to be deployed only within German territory.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of the KSK was envisaged after Germany suffered
the embarrassment of not having appropriate forces to rescue 11
employees of the Deutsche Welle state radio station who were
trapped in Rwanda during the civil war three years ago, according
to reports of the German news agency DPA.
</P>
<P>
Bonn had to ask Belgium to send its paratroopers to evacuate
those people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
