<HEADLINE> Greek Official on Multinational Force Locations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The locations of deployment of the
the multinational security force in Albania were a matter to be
decided by the countries participating in the force, said a Greek
Foreign Ministry official today.
</P>
<P>
George Papandreou, alternate foreign minister of Greece, told
reporters that from the outset, Greece had not set as a condition
for participating in the force that Athens would decide where its
contingent was to be stationed.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Greece had proposed its troops be based in
central Albania because Athens believed it could make a
particularly important contribution there.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that this position reflected the
responsibility with which Athens was confronting the issue of the
ethnic Greek minority, about 300,000 living in southern Albania,
and Greek-Albanian relations in general.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the United Nations gave the green light for the
formation of a 5,000-strong force, half of which will be deployed
and half held in reserve, to protect humanitarian relief
operations in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 Greek troops are expected to participate in the
U.N.-mandated operation which will last for three months.
Countries such as Italy, France, Spain, Hungary, Romania and
Turkey will also send troops to the strife-ridden Albania.
</P>
</TEXT>
