<HEADLINE> Immigration Law Goes Into Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The new immigration law went
into effect today as scheduled after a U.S. Court of Appeals
rejected a U.S. district judge's ruling that would have delayed
the implementation for four days.
</P>
<P>
Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) spokesman Brian
Jordan said the U.S. Court of Appeals, acting on an appeal by the
Justice Department, overturned at 1 a.m. the ruling of Emmet
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua, El
Salvador, and Costa Rica were meeting with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to make a plea that no collective deportations
are carried out under the law enacted today.
</P>
<P>
The ministers met Monday with Attorney General Janet Reno, who
repeated the Clinton administration's line that there will be no
massive deportations.
</P>
<P>
Sullivan had ruled in favor of the American Civil Liberties
Union and immigrants' advocacies who argued the INS had had no
time to polish the regulations to implement the 1996 Immigration
Reform Act, and that the public and immigration lawyers didn't
have a chance to comment on the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Immigration officials had said Sullivan's decision would cause
"wide-scale confusion (and) significantly undermine" the
administration's ability to enforce the new law.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of immigrants, mostly from Latin America
and the Caribbean, fear they will be rounded up and deported.
</P>
<P>
The new immigration legislation combined with the 1996 social
welfare reform denies social services to illegal immigrants and
sharply reduce benefits to legal residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
