<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Defends US Vetoes to UN Israel Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today defended his U.N. chief's move to veto two Security Council
resolutions condemning Israel's decision to build a Jewish
neighborhood in traditionally Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The vetoes did not evidence support in the United States for
the decision to the building to go forward at Har Homa (in east
Jerusalem)," Clinton said during a photo session with King Hussein
of Jordan at the White House.
</P>
<P>
He was answering a question from a reporter who believed the
U.S. move was "a departure from long-standing policy" for the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We vetoed the resolutions for two reasons," Clinton said. "One
is we don't think that they're very helpful to the peace process;
and second is there was language in both resolutions which we
believe prejudiced the final status negotiations against the
Israelis."
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with King Hussein of Jordan at the White
House, Clinton said "this is a difficult time for the peace
process" and he had a lot to talk about with the king, who arrived
in Washington today via New York.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes between Israelis and Palestinians on the West
Bank have continued for 13 consecutive days, in which
Palestinians, outraged by Israelis bulldozers moving into Arab
east Jerusalem to break ground for Jewish housing constructions,
went on to the street for demonstrations against Israel's move
that was obviously in violation of the Oslo agreement, and were
confronted with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Dodging about a question whether Israel's attempt to establish
the Jewish settlement was the "real cause of violence," Clinton
said what the Israelis and Palestinians had to do "is to restore
the environment of security and of confidence so we can go forward
with the negotiating process."
</P>
<P>
"Let me say that, unambiguously, a precondition of going
forward is a commitment to zero tolerance for terrorism, for
making the best effort," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he held extensive meetings with U.S. peace broker
Dennis Ross Monday and again today to discuss the volatile
situations in the Middle East. Ross was dispatched to the region
last week to hold talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in an attempt to salvage
the tottering peace process because of defying of
Israeli-Palestinian agreements. But he returned to Washington
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also did not rule out a plan to send Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to the Middle East "at a right time."
</P>
<P>
"I certainly want her to go.... We want it to be a trip that
will actually be part of a strategy designed to move the process
forward," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters he had some ideas on dissolving the
recent crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We've got some ideas about it, but I want to talk to the king
about it first. And you may be sure we're working on it," he said.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein told reporters that he hoped to discuss with
Clinton what further steps could be take to achieve the goal of
peace in the Middle East through negotiations, which have been
broken down because of Israel's decision to build the Jewish
settlement in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein was the last of four Middle East leaders coming to
Washington for talks with Clinton on the peace process. The first
who came here was Netanyahu, who then was followed by Arafat and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
