<HEADLINE> Sudanese FM: Ties With Egypt Beset by Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian-Sudanese relations are
still beset with some differences, Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali
Osman Mohammed Taha said here today.
</P>
<P>
Taha, at a news conference this evening before leaving for
home, said that with the passage of time, these relations can be
upgraded into positive cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said he updated his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa on the
peace agreement recently signed in Sudan on the sidelines of the
just-concluded Arab League Ministerial Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese top diplomat said Sudan is facing "foreign
aggression," indirectly rejected Egypt's early statement that
the fightings in its southern neighbor is a domestic affair.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese troops and rebel forces have been engaged in
military clashes since early January. The Sudanese government has
accused Uganda, Eritrea and Ethiopia of sponsoring rebel attacks
along their borders with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government initialled a peace agreement last
Wednesday with the rebels and the final signing is expected to
take place on April 10, amid hope that end of the conflicts might
be near.
</P>
<P>
Cairo-Khartoum ties have been cool since Egypt accused Sudan of
having orchestrated the 1995 failed attempt on the life of
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa and granting
asylum to Egyptian extremists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
