<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government, Rebels Initial Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
initialed a peace agreement with the rebels, who have broken away
from their leader John Garang, said reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The final signing is expected to take place on April 10 in
Khartoum, capital of Sudan, Egypt's MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed a week ago, has not met all the rebels'
demands, as it was agreed that the transitional period will be
four years. But the report did not say where the agreement was
reached.
</P>
<P>
Government sources were quoted as ruling out the idea of
conducting a referendum on self-determination in south Sudan,
replacing it by a "yes or no" option on getting the south unified
with the north,
</P>
<P>
In case the majority are in support of unification, the two
sides should meet with each other again to look into the measures
to be taken, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The MENA report said the Sudanese government has rejected that
the headquarters of the proposed coordinatory council be seated
in Juba on the southern tip of the country, advising the
signatories to locate the council in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been raging in the war-torn country since the
beginning of this year between the government forces on the one
side and the northern opposition parties of the National
Democratic Alliance and rebel troops of the Sudan People's
Liberation Army led by John Garang on the other in the Sudanese
eastern and southern border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
