<HEADLINE> Tanzania-China Friendship Textile Co Ltd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The first joint venture between
China and Tanzania in the industrial field, Tanzania-China Friendship
Textile Co. Ltd, was officially launched here today.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Industries and Trade William Shija and Chinese
Ambassador to Tanzania Xie Yukun cut ribbon at the launching
ceremony here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Adressing at the function, Shija highly commended the Chinese
government and people for their brotherly assistance to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Shija recalled that China helped Tanzania build the Friendship
Textile Mill of Tanzania in 1968. Its production had been good up
to 1980. However, he said, the production has declined in the
1980s and the 1990s, due to lack of funds and poor management.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government agreed to help rehabilitate the
mill, and the Dieqiu Textiles Company of China decided a year ago
to run the mill jointly with Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to a contract, signed in March, 1996, Dieqiu owns a 51
percent share while the Tanzanian government has a 49 pecent share in
the joint venture, Tanzania-China Friendship Textile Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed his belief that the joint venture,
to be managed by Chinese experts, will be
successful because China is one of the advanced countries in
textile industry in the world.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador Xie Yukun called for scientific
management, discipline, deligence and co-operation to enhance
production in the company.
</P>
<P>
He said the joint venture would also help cement the existing
ties between China and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The General Manager of the company, Yu Kaiming, callled on the
government to reduce the 30 percent sales tax on textiles, saying
it was too high.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to properly tax textile importers.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people attended the launching ceremony. They
included Deputy Minister for Industries and Trade Shamin Khan,
other high-ranking officials from the ministry and the Chinese
Embassy, and representatives of workers of the textile factory.
