<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York City Sees Continued Decline in Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- New York City, which experienced
a sharp drop in crimes last year, saw continued decline in crimes
in the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Reports of seven major crimes -- murder, rape, robbery,
assault, burglary, grand larceny and car theft -- dropped by 15.6
percent over the same period of last year, according to
preliminary police statistics released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Murder and car theft, two of the crimes that most frightened
and annoyed New Yorkers, dropped more precipitously than any other
major crimes. A total of 194 people were reported killed during
the first three months of the year, a 27 percent decrease over the
corresponding period of last year. And 13,004 cars were reported
stolen during the above-mentioned period, down 20 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Criminologists noted that the decline of crack, the economic
upturn and the more aggressive policing strategies are the major
factors that attributed to the continued decline in crimes in the
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
