<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Hong Kong Immigrants to Return to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Hong Kong Chinese
who have immigrated into Canada in recent years are returning to
Hong Kong, the Financial Post newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 10,000 people will return to Hong Kong
this year, mainly from Vancouver, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Evidence of the emigration is everywhere in Vancouver. Scores
of 1-million-dollar homes and exclusive apartments are up for sale
and members of the Chinese community talk about friends and family
members who have decided to go home.
</P>
<P>
Most seem to be recent immigrants who have not been able to
adapt or graduates who see better career opportunities in Hong
Kong. Many are returning to find work or to take advantage of Hong
Kong's buoyant real estate and stock markets.
</P>
<P>
"People are gaining back confidence and they would obviously
prefer to do business in Hong Kong rather than in Canada," said
William Yee of Vancouver's Chinese Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
As the exodus gathers pace, fewer wealthy Hong Kong immigrants
are arriving in Vancouver, said the Canadian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the authorities granted 1,500 investor class and
entrepreneur class visas to Hong Kong residents with declared net
assets totaling 2.9 billion dollars. But only 574 visas were
awarded in the first nine months of 1996, involving assets of 756
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The property market has already felt the effects of wealthy
Chinese returning to Hong Kong. Scores of homes are up for sale
and prices have dropped as much as 20 percent in the city's
upmarket west side, where many Chinese settled.
</P>
<P>
There are about half a million Hong Kong immigrants in Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
