<HEADLINE> Arab States Request UN Special Session on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Arab states requested an
emergency special session of the U.N. General Assembly to consider
the illegal Israeli actions in occupied east Jerusalem and the
rest of the occupied Palestinian territory, a U.N. spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Fred Eckhard said that chairman of the Group of Arab
States put forward the request in a letter to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nasser bin Hamad Al-Khalifa, ambassador of Qatar and chairman
of the Group of Arab States, asked for convening the emergency
special session pursuant to General Assembly resolution 377 (V),
known as the "Uniting for Peace" formula.
</P>
<P>
He said in the letter that Arab states believed "the illegal
Israeli measures represent a threat to international peace and
security as they endanger the Middle East peace process and are
also in violation of international law and relevant Security
Council and General Assembly resolutions."
</P>
<P>
He criticized the two successive vetoes cast by the United
States on March 7 and 21 in the Security Council to prevent action
on Israel's plan to build homes on occupied land.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly adopted a resolution on March 13 by 130
votes to two with two abstentions, calling on Israel to abandon
the building project.
</P>
<P>
The special session would be called within 24 hours when the
secretary-general determined that the majority of the member
states supported the request, Eckhard noted.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials estimated that the special session might take
place next week, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
