<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Appeals for 68.2-Mln-Dlr Humanitarian Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations today appealed
for 68.2 million U.S. dollars to meet the humanitarian needs in
Sierra Leone following five years of civil conflict, which
formally ended with the signing the Abidjan peace accord on
November 30, 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Department of Humanitarian
Affairs, about 517,000 out of the estimated 1.6 million displaced
people have returned to their areas of origin since late last year
when the government of Sierra Leone, UN agencies and
non-governmental organizations began to make joint efforts to
promote the advantages of timely resettlement.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian program reflected in the appeal, for the
period from March 1997 through February 1998, is designed to
promote the consolidation of peace and to assist the affected
population in attaining higher levels of self-sufficiency.
Accordingly, food aid will be provided to sustain people displaced
or impoverished by the war, to facilitate their return to their
communities and to support them while they strive to produce their
own sustenance. Similarly, direct benefits such as nutritional
supplements, vaccines and educational services for displaced
children will be combined with measures to build up the local
capacity for the delivery of these services.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian activities are aimed to provide a basic
foundation for the National Resettlement, Rehabilitation and
Reconstruction Program launched by the government of Sierra Leone
in September 1996. The appeal is designed to provide a basic
safety-net for the war-affected and returnees, while the program
establishes conditions for people to resume their livelihoods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
