<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Indicates Personal Commitment to Mideast Pease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton today
indicated he would personally intervene in the recent crisis in
the Middle East, caused by Israel's earthmovers entering east
Jerusalem for Jewish housing construction, so that the peace
process could be salvaged from breaking down.
</P>
<P>
"I'm prepared personally to do anything I can to get this
process back on track and move it forward, but I think the less I
say about it, the more likely I am to have some success in doing
that," he said after his 45-minute meeting with King Hussein of
Jordan at the White House, at which they conferred on how to halt
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes between Israelis and Palestinians on the West
Bank have continued for 13 consecutive days, in which
Palestinians, outraged by Israelis bulldozers moving into Arab
east Jerusalem to break ground to build 6,500 Jewish homes, went
on to the street in protest against Israel's move that was
obviously in violation of Israeli-Palestinian peace agreements,
and confronted with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"We've got to try to keep the lid on things over there.... It
is not going to be easy," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He said he looked forward to meeting Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu if he could come to Washington this weekend to
confer with representatives of the American Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
A White House official said earlier that it was not certain if
Netanyahu would make the trip, but Clinton said, "I understand
he's coming and I certainly hope to see him. I expect to see
him.... I think it's important for us to talk and I's glad he's
coming."
</P>
<P>
At the start of his meeting with King Hussein, Clinton told
reporters that he had some ideas on dissolving the recent crisis,
and he would first confer the king before making any announcement.
</P>
<P>
"We've got some ideas about it, but I want to talk to the king
about it first. And you may be sure we're working on it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said before his meeting with King Hussein that it was
"a difficult time for the peace process."
</P>
<P>
King Hussein agreed, saying: "We are certainly passing through
a difficult stage."
</P>
<P>
Clinton would not say that Israel's attempt to establish the
Jewish settlement was what a reporter called "the real cause of
violence," but only emphasized the necessity of restoring "the
environment of security and of confidence" in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Let me say that, unambiguously, a precondition of going
forward is a commitment to zero tolerance for terrorism, for
making the best effort," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he held extensive meetings with U.S. peace broker
Dennis Ross Monday and again today to discuss the volatile
situations in the Middle East. Ross was dispatched to the region
last week to hold talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Netanyahu in an attempt to salvage the tottering peace process
because of Israel's defying of peace agreements. But he returned
to Washington empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not rule out a plan to send Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to the Middle East "at a right time."
</P>
<P>
"I certainly want her to go.... We want it to be a trip that
will actually be part of a strategy designed to move the process
forward," the president said.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein told reporters that he hoped to discuss with
Clinton what further steps could be taken to achieve the goal of
peace in the Middle East through negotiations, which have been
broken down because of Israel's decision to build the Jewish
settlement in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein was the last of four Middle East leaders coming to
Washington for talks with Clinton on the peace process. The first
who came here was Netanyahu, who then was followed by Arafat and
Egyptian President Hosni [0;1;7mMubarak[0;1m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
