<HEADLINE> US B-2 Bombers Becomes Operational: Pentagon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. B-2 "stealth" bomber,
capable of dropping conventional and nuclear bombs, has become
operational, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of the planned 21 planes have been delivered to
Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure the U.S. taxpayers that this is the most
up-to-date heavy bomber flying in the world today. It has stealth
capability," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
The two-billion U.S. dollar planes, designed to foil radar,
were capable of worldwide missions carrying 900 kg conventional
bombs that are guided to their targets by space satellites.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force originally planned to purchase 50 such
bombers, which were designed during the Cold War period against
the former Soviet Union, but decided to buy 21 due to the high
expenses of the plane and the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
"The Air Force has made the decision that 21 planes will be
enough for them to meet their needs in conjunction with other
heavy bombers we already have," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force currently has nearly 100 B-1 bombers, and
several hundred B-52 bombers still in operation, according to
the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
