<HEADLINE> 31 Bosnian War Orphans Return Home From Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-one war orphans who were
evacuated to Germany from the war-torn Bosnia over four years ago
returned to their home country today, said German media reports.
</P>
<P>
The 31 orphans, aged between five and 10 years, were among the
42 children evacuated from Sarajevo in August 1992 in a
controversial move sponsored by two local parliament members of
the eastern German Saxony-Anhalt state. The other 11 had already
returned home earlier.
</P>
<P>
The two German local parliament members had been criticized at
that time for organizing the evacuation single-handedly without
advice from the German federal government and the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). Two babies were killed by
sniper fire during the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
Escorted by their German teachers, the 31 Bosnian children were
flown by a chartered plane from Berlin to Sarajevo where they will
start their new life with the help of the German teachers, German
television reports said.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, all the boys and girls, who had been
educated in German kindergartens and schools, received intensive
lessons on their mother tongue. They were also prepared to adjust
to the new environment with the help of psychologists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
