<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, EU End Talks on Meat, Poultry Without Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government announced
today imposition of meat inspection standards on the European
Union countries' meat and poultry after the two sides failed in
their negotiations on meat and poultry shipments.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman made the announcement
that could curb as much as 300 million U.S. dollars of meat and
poultry shipments from the 15-nation EU in the wake of talks on
common requirements, a "veterinary equivalence arrangement"
concluded without agreement. The bilateral talks had continued for
almost three years.
</P>
<P>
The measures that could cause as much as 1 billion dollar loss
in the meat and poultry trade between the United States and the
Western European market.
</P>
<P>
The EU had also requested the United States and other countries
must meet its new standards taking effect today and thus threaten
millions of dollars worth of U.S. meat and poultry exports.
</P>
<P>
EU spokesman Gerard Kiely said as much as 700 million dollars a
year in American meat product exports could be disrupted by the
new European food safety criteria.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. agriculture secretary also acknowledged that the new
European rules will adversely affect U.S. exports to the Western
European nations.
</P>
<P>
"Under these circumstances, as previously announced, the United
States, as of April 1 will begin to implement a system that will
require EU meat exports to comply with U.S. inspection
requirements," Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials had warned that EU meat and poultry would be
subject to U.S. inspections, which would disrupt shipments to the
United States. EU exports to the United States exceed 300 million
dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Members of the EU are Austria, Belgium, Britain, Denmark,
Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Portugal, Spain and Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
