<HEADLINE> Khan Advances in British Squash Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Jansher Khan beat Ireland's Derek
Ryan to move one step closer to the defence of his British Open
title in Cardiff on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago the legendary Pakistani suffered a startling
defeat to Ryan in the British League match but there was no doubt
who was the master this time as Jansher won 15-7, 15-6, 15-9.
</P>
<P>
Ryan took Jansher to a hard four games a year ago, but although
the contest lasted only two minutes short of an hour on this
occasion he never looked like discomforting Jansher.
</P>
<P>
The first game was peppered with lets and long rallies, Jansher
going to 5-3, 8-4,and 13-6 before taking it characteristically,
punctuating a rally of stealthy sparring with a sudden fierce
kill.
</P>
<P>
That game lasted 25 minutes and sapped Ryan's strength. It
needed a late run of four points by him to add respectability to
the scoreline.
</P>
<P>
Jansher next plays Australian qualifier Joe Kneipp.
</P>
<P>
In a noisy match which sometimes threatened to disturb
proceedings on the next court, Kneipp beat 15th seeded Paul
Gregory in straight games 15-12, 15-11 and 15-7.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a dispute over the rules led to the world number four
from England Chris Walker reaching the second round without
hitting a ball.
</P>
<P>
His opponent Martin Heath of Scotland withdrew with a foot
injury, and the English Squash Rackets Association tournament
manager Don Sanderson was prepared to replace him with Billy
Haddrell of Australia, according to the lucky loser rule in the
manual.
</P>
<P>
But John Nimick, the Executive Director of the Professional
Squash Association which runs the circuit, invoked a separate
rule which says a player withdrawing on-site at a tournament is
entitled to his loser's prize money points.
</P>
<P>
These were duly given to Heath even though the world number 19
said he was prepared to forgo them.
</P>
<P>
Walker, who recently posed nude because even as England number
one he does not have a shoe or clothing contract, will therefore
play his opening match in the second round against Wales' David
Evans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
