<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Birds Spotted in Chinese North Port City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGHUANGDAO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A large number of rare grey
cranes have been spotted on the Qilihai Lake in Changli
County of north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, there are more than 320 grey cranes
flying in the area in three groups. Local residents predict more
cranes will appear in April and May.
</P>
<P>
The grey crane is a rare waterbird that is under state
protection. Only 200,000 grey cranes currently live in the world,
with 10,000 in China.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a big surprise to see so many grey cranes in just
one place," said Xu Weishou, vice president of China
Ornithological Society.
</P>
<P>
With an area of 150,000 sq kms and near the Bohai Bay, Qilihai
Lake, with rich freshwater and biological diversity, is the
biggest natural lagoon in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
