<HEADLINE> FIFA Suspend Portuguese Referees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- FIFA has suspended Portuguese
referees from international matches until a dispute between the
country's referees' association and soccer federation is settled.
</P>
<P>
"The dispute between the two associations has led to a
situation where FIFA decided to suspend the referees from
international duty," FIFA spokesman Andreas Herren said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as the dispute is settled the situation will be
reviewed."
</P>
<P>
The swearing-in of the seven-strong referees' council of the
Portuguese Soccer Federation in March was suspended against its
wishes after the referees' association lodged a complaint in a
civil court over an appointment.
</P>
<P>
The referees' association said in the complaint that Avelino
Ferreira Torres was not eligible for a seat on the council because
he did not have a "clean record".
</P>
<P>
Ferreira Torres was suspended from administrative duties for
six months in 1990 for allegedly making unethical remarks in a
press interview.
</P>
<P>
Both national associations are holding talks to resolve the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
Herren said the immediate impact of the FIFA ruling was that
Portuguese referee Jorge Monteiro Coroado would not take charge of
the World Cup qualifier between Lithuania and Romania in Vilnius
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He has been replaced by German Edgar Steinborn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
