<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina will be able to produce 30 tons of
gold a year before the year 2000, becoming one of the biggest gold
producers in Latin America and the world, even though its current
production is 750 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of the country's mining and private
enterprises said that thanks to the start of mining projects in
several provinces, the production of gold will increase to 7,000
kilograms in 1997, to 25,000 in 1998 and to 30,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) will
grant Costa Rica a loan of 80 million U.S. dollars for the
construction of the Toro II hydroelectrical plant, the Costa Rican
Electricity Institute (ICE) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Toro plant, located on the Cuarto de Grecia River in
northern Costa Rica, will have an annual generating capacity of
311 GWH, representing 10 percent of the total installed capacity
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the plant will cost 122 million dollars, of
which 65 percent will be financed by the IDB.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's industrial productivity increased by 78
percent in 1996 over the previous year, said the National Center
of Technology and Industrial Productivity (CNTPI)
</P>
<P>
The CNTPI said the growth was the result of higher investments
in new technologies, of the training efforts that were made during
those years and of a CNTPI integrated development project in
quality and productivity.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Foreign capital directly invested in Venezuela in
1996 increased by 27 percent over the previous year, the
Superintendency of Foreign Investments (SIEX) said.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of foreign investments in 1996 was about 7.5
billion U.S. dollars, the SIEX said.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum sector received the biggest volume of capital,
followed by such sectors as commerce, agriculture and livestock
breeding, construction, transportation and electrical and water
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Earthquake Hits Chile, Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake hit northern Chile
and southern Peru today, causing landslides but no injuries were
reported.
</P>
<P>
The tremor, which struck at 2:33 p.m. local time (1833 GMT),
measured 6.2 on the Richter scale, and had its epicenter in the
Atacama Desert east of the port of Arica, according to a statement
issued by the Earthquake Institute of Chilean University.
</P>
<P>
Local radio also reported that the tremor had caused brief
power cuts in several towns.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Geophysical Institute of Peru said the quake
and two aftershocks ranged in magnitude from 4.6 to five on the
Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
The first quake was centred in the Pacific Ocean 30 kilometers
southwest of Tacna, and the epicenter of the second, measuring 4.6
on the Richter scale, was 10 kilometers east of the city. Tacna is
about 1,350 kilometers south of Lima.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian radio said there were no immediate reports of
injuries in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maradona Refuses to Rejoin Boca Juniors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Diego Maradona has refused to
rejoin his Argentinian side Boca Juniors blaming the team's
sponsors for his decision.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old former World Cup winner, who was sent home in
disgrace from the 1994 World Cup after testing positive for drugs,
had said on Monday night that he was on the verge of returning to
the club, whom he had not played for since August because of a row
with the club president Mauricio Macri.
</P>
<P>
However, he laid the blame for his change of mind at the feet
of Nike, whose kit the team wears, saying that he would find it
difficult to wear the strip anyway but that his contract with a
rival of Nike's, Puma, would not allow him to appear at press
conferences in Nike kit. 
</P>
