<DOCNO> XIE19970402.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Countries Protest Brazil's Import Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The governments of
Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay today expressed their protest
against the Brazilian policy on import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Brazilian government announced restrictions on
the financing of imports in order to reduce its trade
deficit. Importers will have to pay for all of imported goods
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The measure will affect 65 percent of the Brazilian imports and
will also harm the interests of Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay,
Brazil's three partners in the Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Argentine Economy Minister Roque Fernandez postponed his visit
to Brazil today to protest against the Brazilian decision.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan Economy Minister Luis Mosca said that the Brazilian
restrictions will affect more than half of its country's exports
to Brazil. The restrictions will harm Uruguay's textile and
clothing manufactures whose exports to Brazil totaled 831 million
U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza accused Brazil of
protectionism within the Mercosur. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
