<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- A circular has been signed and issued by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin, also chairman of the Military Commission of the CPC
Central Committee to award a group of PLA units and individuals
Citations for Merit.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin, in meeting with visiting
Australian Prime Minister John Howard Tuesday, said that China and
Australia should further their cooperation based on mutual respect
and with an eye to the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed the wish during a meeting with Howard, who is
on his first official visit to China as Australian Prime Minister,
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin yesterday hailed the signing of a
memorandum of understanding on a submarine optical cable project
between the US's AT&AMP;T and China.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with AT&AMP;T's Chairman Robert Allen in Beijing,
Jiang wished the Sino-American project smooth sailing and praised
AT&AMP;T for having established good cooperative ties with China over
the past several years.
</P>
<P>
-- The average speed of China's trains have been upgraded from
48.1 to 54.9 km per hour, and the maximum speed of long-distance
passenger trains, 97.6 km per hour, while the price of tickets
remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The government has launched a plan to virtually eliminate
poverty in China by the year 2000, and 17 million people are
expected to be lifted out of poverty each year.
</P>
<P>
-- China yesterday issued an order to ban imports of hogs,
oxen, sheep and other artiodactyls (two-toed ruminants) and their
byproducts from Taiwan, since a recent outbreak of
foot/hoof-and-mouth disease occurred on the island.
</P>
<P>
-- China is to host the world's third largest show featuring
the latest advances in the metals industry.  
</P>
